<HEAD>Kennedys, Nephew and Uncle, Bring Crowd to Its Feet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOPS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with reax to Jackson at
convention; PICKS UP 2nd graf pvs bgng, `The delegates'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The young man once known to the country as `` John-John,'' son of the Democrats' martyred president, brought convention delegates to their feet cheering Tuesday night and told them: `` Because of you, he is with us still.'' And later, the five children of <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> introduced their father, the candidate, to a hall so crowded they locked the doors. Hundreds of delegates, reporters, and convention guests were stopped by a police line after the fire marshal ordered that The Omni arena could hold no more. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> shared his big moment before the convention with the woman whose refusal to give up her seat on a bus in <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, more than a quarter century ago began the turnaround in American race relations. `` All of you think you are seated,'' he said as he introduced <PERSON> Rosa </PERSON> <PERSON> Parks </PERSON>. `` But you're really standing on someone's shoulders.'' The convention hall was a waving sea of red `` <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON>!'' signs as the runner-up in the nominee race appeared, after his children introduced him one-by-one. Not a single blue sign for <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the Democratic nominee-to-be, could be seen. The delegates to the Democratic National Convention had been a rather undemonstrative lot until they welcomed <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> with a two-minute standing ovation. `` Over a quarter century ago, my father stood before you to accept the nomination for president,'' said the 27-year-old <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>. And then he introduced his uncle, who he said inspired his generation. As if to show that the <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> name still carries magic, the delegates stood and cheered again, for Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, the dead president's brother and <PERSON> John-John </PERSON>'s Uncle Teddy. It was a fitting prelude for the big show yet to come, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s closing speech of his long campaign for the presidency <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, a spellbinding speaker, did n't disappoint the convention. Until he arrived, many seats were still empty. Like magic, they filled. `` Where was <PERSON> George </PERSON>?'' he asked repeatedly. And the delegates responded with a cascading chant, `` Where was <PERSON> George </PERSON>? Where was <PERSON> George </PERSON>?'' Said Kennedy: `` We all know the answer to all these questions. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is the man who is never there. And he wo n't be there after the clock strikes noon on Jan. 20, 1989.'' In fact, Sen. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> was the second speaker of the evening to bring up `` Where was <PERSON> George </PERSON>?'' Earlier in the evening, Rep. <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> recited a similar litany and got a similar response. The two speakers may have been telegraphing a battle cry for the campaign to come. The question caused banners to bob up and down in the hall. The red `` <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON>!'' signs as well as the red-white and blue posters saying `` <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> for President,'88.''
</TEXT>
