<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Communist rebels rejected new peace talks with President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> as a `` farce'' Monday, charging her government and the military merely wanted to trap leaders of the 19-year-old insurgency. Self-styled communist rebels meanwhile killed a provincial official Monday and a guerrilla spokesman warned of more killings as long as the government fails, he said, to prosecute human rights violators in the military. The general command of the communist <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, in a statement sent by courier to news agencies, claimed Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s government lost its credibility following the collapse of peace talks last year Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> has said she would agree to new peace talks if the rebels made the first move. <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramos </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and the 250,000-member armed forces would abide by her decision. <PERSON> Ramos </PERSON> earlier turned down the possibility of reviving the talks, saying it would only give the rebels time to regroup. `` The president has spoken,'' <PERSON> Ramos </PERSON> told reporters. `` I do n't think there is anyone that will oppose any objective such as obtaining peace, but it must be peace with justice and honor. The rebel statement was in response to a call last week by the influential <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bishops </ORGANIZATION>' Conference of the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> for the government and the guerrillas to call for a new cease-fire and revive peace talks. `` History repeats itself twice: the first as tragedy, the second as farce,'' the statement said. `` We can not ... respond positively to a call for a new cease-fire that will mean the annihilation of the revolutionary movement and its mass base. We have learned our lessons well from the duplicity of the Aquino government and its military establishment.'' The rebels accused the government of insincerity and charged that `` what the government and the military establishment sought to lay down was a trap that played on the good faith of the leaders of the revolutionary movement.'' About five members of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and dozens of its regional leaders were captured by the military in raids after the 60-day cease-fire lapsed in February 1987. On Sunday, the rebels' southern <LOCATION> Luzon </LOCATION> command said it was agreeable to peace talks in principle but claimed the government was setting unacceptable conditions. In a related development, police said two men who claimed to be communist guerrillas barged into a government office on Monday in <LOCATION> Lucena </LOCATION>, 60 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>, and shot dead city councilor <PERSON> Donaldo </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfaro </PERSON>, 54. <PERSON> Alfaro </PERSON> belonged to a government group organized to help the military curb rebel infiltration of local neighborhoods. <PERSON> Arnel </PERSON> <PERSON> Sandoval </PERSON>, spokesman of the <ORGANIZATION> Alex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boncayao </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brigade </ORGANIZATION>, justified the guerrillas' continuing attacks on police, soldiers and government officials by claiming the government failed to prosecute `` notorious police and military human rights violators.'' The brigade is a Manila-based unit of the rebel army that has claimed responsibility for killing more than 100 police, soldiers and officials during the past year. In <LOCATION> Bulacan </LOCATION> province, police Monday arrested two suspected rebels who killed a policeman a day earlier in <LOCATION> Baliwag </LOCATION>, just north of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>. A gunman Monday fatally shot Vice Mayor <PERSON> Daud </PERSON> <PERSON> Talib </PERSON> on the island of <LOCATION> Jolo </LOCATION>, about 600 miles south of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>, police said. The area is a stronghold of Moslem separatist guerrillas.
