<HEAD>Effectiveness of U.S. Aid To Egypt Questioned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two government reports question the effectiveness of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assistance to <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> and cast doubt on whether the aid has brought about policy changes sought by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. A <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> study of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid to seven countries, of which <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> is the most populous, concluded that the <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> has had `` mixed success'' in encouraging foreign policy reforms. Another report, from AID Inspector General <PERSON> Hebert </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Beckington </PERSON>, criticized the use of $ 1.5 billion worth of machinery and equipment sent to <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> between 1975 and 1986. <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> got $ 819.7 million in `` economic support funds'' from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in fiscal 1987, second only to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. AID spokesman <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Leary </PERSON> said Monday that $ 115 million of the aid was transferred in cash to the government of President <PERSON> Hosni </PERSON> <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON>. Most of the rest was spent on projects designed to raise the country's standard of living. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report said the cash transfer to <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> was based on a document that described broad policy changes that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government expected from <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> but gave no details on how progress would be measured. The report, dated June 29 and made public this month, added that while the document listed Egyptian policy reforms since the previous transfer, it did not explain their meaning or how they related to what the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> sought. `` <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> has not moved quickly enough to adopt the economic reforms necessary to address the numerous and costly inefficiencies that pervade the Egyptian economy,'' it said. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, in a comment included in the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report, said there are countries where setting reform targets in advance will fuel political opposition on the grounds that foreigners are dominating economic policy. `` In some situations a less specific economic reform program ... may be preferable to a highly specific program with unrealistic expectations,'' <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> McAllister </PERSON>, assistant secretary of state for economic affairs, stated in the report. The AID report on <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>'s use of U.S.-financed machinery and equipment blamed the inability of the Egyptian government, AID and contractors to coordinate procurement with actual construction. `` Large amounts were either not being used or used at levels much below what was anticipated,'' the report said of the equipment. The report, issued about the same time as the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> document, also cited `` the limited capability of government of <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> entities to operate and maintain machinery and equipment.''
