<HEAD>End of Meese Investigation Looses War of Words</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> has nothing but angry words for a $ 1.7 million investigation into his ethics that he believes both vindicates him and will allow him to ask the government to pay his legal fees. Independent counsel <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> ended a 14-month investigation of <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> by issuing a lengthy report Monday while making no formal charges. But the report precipitated an immediate war of words between <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> and his lawyers and <PERSON> McKay </PERSON>. After court personnel handed out 6-inch-thick piles of documents to more than 100 journalists who had waited in line as long as 2 -LCB- hours at the federal court building, the combatants began a string of news conferences at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> lawyer <PERSON> Nathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewin </PERSON> compared <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> to a `` hit-and-run'' driver for accusing the attorney general of crimes and then running away from filing charges. `` It was a cheap shot,'' <PERSON> Lewin </PERSON> said. He called the investigation `` a total bust, a colossal blunder'' and scoffed at the prosecutor's 814-page report, downplaying the length of his own filing which was nearly as thick but printed on only one side of each page. <PERSON> Lewin </PERSON> said his rebuttal, with sections titled `` Fishing in Foreign Policy Water,'' `` The Empty Net'' and `` Procrastination is not Willfulness,'' was more readable than <PERSON> McKay </PERSON>'s. <PERSON> Lewin </PERSON> accused <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> of stretching statutes `` beyond what any reasonable prosecutor would do,'' of trying to make an <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> pipeline project look like `` the opening of a McDonald's franchise in <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>'' and of making groundless accusations to justify the high cost of his fruitless investigation. An hour later, <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> held his own news conference and repeated for television cameras the accusations made against <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> in his report: that <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> filed a false tax return, missed a tax filing deadline and dealt with two separate matters that might affect the telephone industry while holding stock in a local telephone company. In addition, <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> accused <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>, both in the report and at the news conference, of insensitivity in dealings as a government official with his close friend, <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>. But <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> said he was using his `` prosecutorial discretion'' not to bring formal charges against <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> because such offenses ordinarily would not lead to prosecution of a person who was not attorney general. He said neither <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> nor his wife, <PERSON> Ursula </PERSON>, had a history of tax evasion and he had no evidence that the attorney general took any of the illegal actions for personal gain or that he deliberately lied. <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> defended the high cost of the investigation. `` I did n't spend it personally,'' he quipped `` I feel confident we have not wasted any government funds, any of the taxpayers' money.'' Asked how he would respond to a lawsuit from <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> if one were filed, he said, `` I've been sued before.'' Finally, <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> strode into the same hall where <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> had just appeared, angrily defending all his actions _ and attacking <PERSON> McKay </PERSON>. `` I'm glad that finally the long ordeal is over,'' <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> said. `` But I'm outraged at the tarnishing of our system of justice that has gone on this afternoon and with the filing of this report by the independent counsel. `` I am appalled that <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> came in front of you and violated every principle of fairness and decency.'' `` I've always acted legally, ethically and properly,'' <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> said, `` and any implication by the independent counsel that I have in any way violated any law is absolutely false.'' <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> said it went against the American judicial system for a court official to publicly accuse someone of a crime and then not file charges. `` If anybody did that in the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, they'd be fired,'' he said. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> said he would not disclose whether he would take any legal action against <PERSON> McKay </PERSON>, but he said he would ask the government to pay his legal expenses which lawyer <PERSON> Lewin </PERSON> said were approaching $ 250,000 six months ago. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> said he did n't know how much the total bill would be.
