 on real property owned by <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>. A separate agreement provided that <PERSON> Bender </PERSON> would advance <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> `` additional funds up to a total of $ 500,000 if a deed of trust in the amount of $ 525,000 were delivered to Mr. <PERSON> Bender </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> said. This was one of several new elements turned up by <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> in his investigation of an incident in 1985 when <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sondra </PERSON> <PERSON> Bender </PERSON>, head of a wealthy <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> real estate family, donated $ 40,000 for Mrs. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s salary. The money was to be paid by the <ORGANIZATION> Multiple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sclerosis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, where she had previously worked as a volunteer. The donation coincided with efforts by a <PERSON> Bender </PERSON> real estate partnership to renew a lucrative lease on office space in the Chester A. Arthur Building for <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> agencies. The lease was renewed at increased rent more than a year after the donation and the <PERSON> Bender </PERSON> partnership quickly sold the building for 60 percent more than it had paid for it about two years earlier. <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> revealed that <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> brought Mrs. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s desire for a paid job to the attention of the Benders. But <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> said he turned up no information that <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> was aware of <PERSON> Bender </PERSON>'s interest in the building or took any role in the lease renewal. In their rebuttal, <PERSON> Bender </PERSON>'s lawyers said he had only a 10 percent to 11 percent interest in the partnership. `` There is no basis in the report for the conclusion ... that Mr. <PERSON> Bender </PERSON> may have had ` ulterior motives' in supporting the November 1985 contribution to the <ORGANIZATION> Multiple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sclerosis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, which was used by that reputable charity to provide employment to <PERSON> Ursula </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Bender </PERSON>'s attorneys wrote. They said the <PERSON> Bender </PERSON> family foundation made the grant because they believed in Mrs. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s abilities to direct development of a job match program for MS victims. <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, said the reference to ulterior motives on <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>'s part is `` gratuitous and without any factual foundation.'' <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> also disclosed that Mrs. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> received $ 15,000 in advances on her salary in both 1985 and 1986. He said the society had no prior history of giving such advances and she testified she needed them to pay bills.
