<FIRST>r i PM-China-MelonMadness     07-19 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Melon Madness,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Loot Watermelons In Annual Summer Rite</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of peasants rioted in a ripe watermelon field and hundreds of urban dwellers looted a melon stand, official reports said, in the latest replay of the melon madness that hits <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> each summer. Participants in similar melon-looting sprees last summer received heavy prison terms, and growers and sellers this year have resorted to hiring police guards _ apparently to little avail. Chinese eat millions of watermelons during the summer _ nearly at a rate of one a day per person in cities _ and some literally go mad over them. In one of the latest looting incidents, about 2,000 peasants swarmed onto a melon field in central <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Henan </LOCATION> province and snatched 500,000 pounds of the juicy fruit in raids July 8 and 9. The Legal Daily -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Fazhi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ribao </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- on Monday carried a blurry picture of dozens of people running through the field, grabbing melons in both arms. It said police tried to restore order but were roughed up by the looters. The growers, 25 peasants who had jointly contracted to plant the land, `` could only put their heads down and cry in the fields,'' the national newspaper said. In a separate incident in northeastern <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Jilin </LOCATION> province, the Legal Daily said hundreds of people in <LOCATION> Songjianghe </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> looted a melon stand over several days in early July, grabbing 60,000 pounds of melon. At first, the melon owner had hired `` protectors'' who fended off thieves, but three men beat up the protectors on July 6 and several hundred people began snatching fruit, the report said. Several suspected looters were arrested but all later were released without charges, it said without elaborating. In last summer's most spectacular melon riot, nearly 100 melon vendors raided a <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> train depot where farmers had brought in melons under contract to other vendors. The raiders beat up some of the farmers and made off with 55,000 pounds of the fruit. Two of the thieves were sentenced to life in prison and six recieved two to 12 years in jail. Also last summer, more than 100 people in <LOCATION> Jilin </LOCATION> province jumped on trucks carrying melons into the provincial capital, <LOCATION> Jilin </LOCATION>, and stole 22,000 pounds. Farmers and bystanders who tried to protect shipment were beaten. <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> authorities announced measures in June to ensure an adequate supply of melons to the city at controlled prices, partly in hopes of heading off violent grabs for the fruit. They lifted the usual ban on bringing tractors and horse-drawn carriages into the city center so that farmers could easily get the melons to market, and set up designated melon marketplaces. So far, no melon violence has been reported in the capital.
</TEXT>
