<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The former second-ranking executive at the global satellite communications network <ORGANIZATION> Intelsat </ORGANIZATION> was arrested in <LOCATION> Aruba </LOCATION> last week and charged with conspiracy to defraud the organization of $ 3.8 million, according to a criminal complaint unsealed Monday in federal court. <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Algrett </PERSON>, fired as deputy director general of <ORGANIZATION> Intelsat </ORGANIZATION> in December 1986, is the fourth person to be charged in a scheme that allegedly defrauded <ORGANIZATION> Intelsat </ORGANIZATION> of $ 5.4 million through a combination of unauthorized payments, bid-rigging, kickbacks and phony commissions. The scheme, said to have been carried out between April 1984 and September 1986, revolved around the construction and financing of the second phase of the new <ORGANIZATION> Intelsat </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Algrett </PERSON> had been living in since January 1987 in <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>. He had sporadic talks with prosecutors and <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents aimed at a plea agreement, but the talks reportedly broke off last month. When <PERSON> Algrett </PERSON> traveled to <LOCATION> Aruba </LOCATION> to meet with a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agent, he was arrested by Aruban authorities and put on a plane for <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, where he was arrested by the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>. He was being held without bond pending a hearing Thursday before a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> magistrate. <ORGANIZATION> Intelsat </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telecommunications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Satellite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, is a consortium of 114 member countries that develops and manages communications satellites.
