<SECOND>PM-Gulf-US Navy, Bjt,0770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Year-Old Convoy Operation Has Reaped Mixed Results</HEAD>
<BYLINE>An AP Extra</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s acceptance of a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> cease-fire plan comes almost exactly a year after the start of the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> convoy operation that led to a massive <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> naval buildup and armed clashes with Iranian forces. <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> officials said they would adopt a `` wait and see'' position on whether, when and how the Persian Gulf-based <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> fleet of about 17 ships would be affected, should the eight years of Iraq-Iran hostilities indeed be ended. As <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>'s surprise announcement was reported by its official <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> on Monday, the 48th <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> convoy of 1988 and the 70th in the past year was en route up the gulf. A spokesman at <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Central Command headquarters in <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, said the U.S.-flagged Kuwaiti gas tanker Gas Princess, escorted by the missile frigate Fahrion, had passed through the Strait of <LOCATION> Hormuz </LOCATION> `` without incident.'' Since the Stars and Stripes was first run up the mast of the renamed supertanker <LOCATION> Bridgeton </LOCATION> on July 21, 1987, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has sailed 42,000 miles, nearly equivalent to twice around the equator, protecting 11 `` reflagged'' Kuwaiti tankers from Iranian attack in the gulf. For <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, `` Operation Earnest Will'' has guaranteed safe transit for millions of tons of oil products that otherwise might not have reached customers in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. For the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, it has meant a grueling test of ships, sailors and technology in a twilight war where threats range from armed speedboats and underwater mines to fast-moving aircraft and dangerously deceptive signals on a radar screen. The escort operation got off to a shaky start when the 401,382-ton <LOCATION> Bridgeton </LOCATION> hit a mine on the first northbound convoy. It is now semi-retired. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Force </LOCATION>, based in the gulf since 1948, grew swiftly from about four ships to the present level, with ten more including an aircraft carrier in a support role in the Arabian Sea. `` A year ago nobody would have predicted we'd have 16 or 17 ships, helicopter carriers, minesweepers, or a lot of other stuff in the gulf,'' an officer said recently. Neither could it be known that the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> would sink or damage six Iranian vessels in a one-day missile war, or that a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cruiser would on July 3 shoot down an Iranian jetliner, killing 290 people. The Pentagon said the cruiser mistook the jetliner for an F-14 fighter jet. The incident is still being investigated. A second Kuwaiti tanker was knocked out of service for five months by an Iranian missile attack on <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s main oil terminal, and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces have had at least three other significant clashes with Iranian craft. About 100 commercial vessels were attacked in the past year, many while sailing to or from <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, which <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> regards as <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s ally in the war. But no U.S-flagged tanker has been molested during a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> convoy. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration said its reflagging policy reflects a long-standing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commitment to freedom of navigation and would blunt <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s effort to expand its influence in the oil-rich region. It has opposed a Soviet-backed proposal for a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> force to replace the seven foreign navies that together have about 30 warships in the gulf. Congressional opponents assailed the reflagging policy as ill-defined and risky, but <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> backers thwarted repeated efforts to invoke the 1973 War Powers Act, which would require <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> withdrawal in 90 days unless <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> agreed otherwise. By rough calculation, the reflagged tankers carry about 20 percent of <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s total oil product exports of 600,000 barrels a day. About a third goes to <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s retail outlets in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the rest to regular customers in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomats say <LOCATION> Kuwaiti </LOCATION> officials have expressed satsifaction with the convoy operation and that deliveries have been smoother since January, when the convoys were increased in frequency but reduced in size, often to one tanker. The Pentagon estimates the cost of its expanded gulf force at $ 20 million a month. Officials say this has been reduced since <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> began providing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warships with free fuel. Nine Americans have been killed in the gulf in the past year, all in helicopter crashes. The missile frigate <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> was nearly sunk by an <LOCATION> Iranian </LOCATION> mine, but officers say the crew's ability to save it validated lessons learned in the May, 1987 Stark disaster, when an errant Iraqi missile attack killed 37 crewmen on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> frigate.
