 With enough cameras present to cover every conceivable angle of the Democratic National Convention, <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> McMahon </PERSON> seemed as obsolete as the flash bulb. But there he was, pencils in hand, sketching the scene on his artist's tablet, recording the proceedings for time, rather than for the moment. `` I do this because an artist sees differently,'' <PERSON> McMahon </PERSON> said. `` I see what all these cameras ca n't. I see around the corners. What I do is not just a snapshot. It's a statement, and the camera usually does n't make a statement.'' <PERSON> McMahon </PERSON>, from <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, has been lending his perspective to the political scene for three decades now. His work is being shown at the CNN Center adjacent to the Omni during the convention. While the convention buzzed around him, <PERSON> McMahon </PERSON> deliberately outlined a picture, looking for nuances and special characteristics of this convention. He placed a computer terminal in the foreground, symbolizing the equipment used to count each state's votes `` I try to bring an element of humor to it,'' <PERSON> McMahon </PERSON> said. `` This is a TV show and I make sure I show TV some way.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Thelma </PERSON> <PERSON> Grundy </PERSON> is giving the Democrats and reporters gathered here some food for thought. Her home-cooking hole-in-the-wall restaurant _ strategically located just blocks from the convention center _ has been spooning up okra, squash, collard greens, ribs and fried chicken so fast she has n't had time to wash the flour from her apron. `` The Lord is good to me,'' she chuckled. Even though a plethora of fancy eateries surround the convention area, <PERSON> Thelma </PERSON>'s Kitchen has served a steady stream of customers. She's been going through a 10-pound crate of okra a day, and at least 30 pounds of chicken. It's the busiest she's even been in 20 years of serving food. `` Business is so rushed I ca n't get to my favorite recipe. It's a special recipe which the Lord gave me and I do n't think anyone else has _ okra cakes A lot of people rave about it.'' The cakes and other southern specialties have spawned a loyal following for <PERSON> Thelma </PERSON>, including local lawyers, businessmen, <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hawks </ORGANIZATION> basketball players and even _ in her pre-fame days _ <PERSON> Vanna </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>. But when it comes to politics, <PERSON> Thelma </PERSON> says she does n't have much stomach for it. `` I like to feed'em, but I do n't much like it otherwise,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 From <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Bigay </PERSON>'s perspective, some 65 feet above the <LOCATION> Omni </LOCATION> floor, the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> has n't been as well organized as, say, a rock concert. <PERSON> Bigay </PERSON> was part of the crew that rigged and focused the hundreds of lights that Democrats hope make their convention shine. He crept across steel trusses hung from the ceiling, used rope-climbing techniques and delighted in thrilling the early-arriving reporters and delegates by descending upside-down. `` They've never done this before, so they were kind of making it up as they went along,'' <PERSON> Bigay </PERSON> said of the organizers. `` But there have n't been any major problems. There's nothing that's not working. And nobody got hurt.''
