<HEAD>Pols Fight for Time on Podium to Impress Folks Back Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Forget all the pomp and preparation, the careful creation of convention images for national consumption. For the raw guts of politics, check the podium schedule. From lowly House challengers to sitting governors, politicians are lobbying fiercely for a moment or two in the spotlight at the Democratic National Convention. The evolving schedule provides clear-cut evidence of the pressure, the winners and the losers. For instance, consider this year's <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> candidates. On the schedule issued Saturday, they were allotted 10 minutes tonight for introductions. In a revision released Monday, the contenders were up to 19 minutes and brief remarks. True, they were scheduled for 4:50 p.m. _ but any exposure is good exposure for challengers fighting for recognition from the home folks who read the local newspaper and watch local TV. `` Podium time is a good boost for these candidates. They'll certainly be covered in their print outlets,'' said <PERSON> Anita </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON>, spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senatorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Campaign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> The success of her group sparked a competitive drive at the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Campaign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. `` We are co-equal branches of government,'' explained committee chairman <PERSON> Beryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON>, D-Ark. His tongue was in his cheek, but he made his point. The revised schedule showed Wednesday proceedings starting 39 minutes earlier than initially planned. More than half an hour was devoted to the House candidates. The House segment on the updated schedule was followed by an all-new governors' segment, as the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZ