 this, <PERSON> McCurry </PERSON> replied, `` Prime time was 8 to 11 last time I checked.'' There were some true casualties, or heroes, forced to sacrifice their precious podium time to the demands of the modern convention. Everyone presenting a section of the platform lost a minute; <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> and Sen. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Conn </LOCATION>., each lost four <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Farmer </PERSON>, the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> finance chairman widely considered a miracle worker, dropped from four minutes to two. And a videotape of praise for <ORGANIZATION> DNC </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Dorothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who calls the roll, got slashed from six minutes to three. The time pressure is such that <PERSON> McCurry </PERSON> would n't even consider a reporter's question about the possibility of roll call rather than voice votes on platform amendments. `` I would n't want to speculate,'' he said, `` on anything that would keep the clocks from running on time.''
