<HEAD>Souvenir Booths Lend Carnival Atmosphere to Convention Site</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 There's more than one way to sell a donkey. You can sling an elephant gun over his shoulder, name him `` Dembo'' and put him on a T-shirt. You can put him on a beer mug or a key chain, or show him kicking an elephant into the next county on the side of a coffee cup. It's all here at row after row of hastily erected souvenir booths near The Omni, site of the Democratic National Convention. There's something for every taste, or lack of it, at this sun-baked bazaar of political kitsch. The <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> has licensing rights on items carrying its official logo, which also has a donkey it. But it's open season in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> this week on other donkey goods There are rolls of toilet paper with `` 1988 Democratic Convention'' -LRB- no donkey -RRB- printed in red, white and blue on each sheet. There are donkey hats, donkey balloons, donkey buttons and a red and white cushion depicting a donkey's generous hindquarters with the helpful legend, `` For Your ...'' There is a donkey on a bib -LRB- `` One For My Baby. 1988 Democratic Convention'' -RRB-, a donkey call for $ 10 and, in a bow to prospective party nominee <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, a stuffed donkey imprinted with `` I Like <PERSON> Mikey </PERSON>.'' Wait, there's more. There are donkey shoelaces, donkey running shorts and an staggering variety of donkey buttons and T-shirts. `` Get your souvenir delegate's button here,'' whooped one pitchman at passing delegates who streamed toward The <LOCATION> Omni </LOCATION> for Monday night's opening session. `` I've got <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> buttons,'' yelled another. How are they selling? `` I do n't have any,'' he admitted. `` I saw the lady wearing one and I wanted her to stop and look at this other stuff.'' `` I've got <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> soda pop,'' shouted a ven