<HEAD>Democrats Show Unity With Quick Adoption of Rules, Credentials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democrats pointed to the quick adoption of major rule changes and the seating of more than 4,000 delegates without a fight as a sign to the nation of their commitment to party unity and hopes for victory in November. `` We decided to go down the road of cooperation and it leads to victory in 1988,'' Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Breaux </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-La </LOCATION>., told delegates on Monday at the start of the 48th Democratic National Convention Rules and credentials, constant points of contention for the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, were resolved weeks before the convention and adopted without a single floor fight or nay vote shortly after <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> gaveled the gathering to order. The speedy adoption _ within 45 minutes _ broke a 25-year Democratic record of fighting. `` We are here to unite tonight,'' said <PERSON> Leroy </PERSON> <PERSON> Irvis </PERSON>, speaker of the <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> House and chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Credentials </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. `` I give you a report and there will be no minority report filed. Every single one has been unanimously approved of. Every single debate has been resolved.'' Negotiators for nominee-to-be <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> reached agreements last month and the rules and credentials committees ratified the results to ensure a unified convention. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had enough delegates to win the nomination plus a 600-delegate cushion that allowed him to concede to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s demands for added delegate representation in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> `` Everybody had to swallow a little to win big,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Schroeder </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Colo </LOCATION>., who served on the Credentials Committee `` We had 24 disagreements and we resolved every single one of those disagreements before we had a formal meeting,'' <PERSON> Irvis </PERSON> told the convention. `` We met in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, without a single problem to resolve.'' And when the delegates responded with unanimous ayes to the credentials report, <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> noted that it was `` the first sign of unanimity and unity.'' On the issue of rules, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> agreed to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s call for a change in the delegate selection process for 1992 to make it more closely conform to the popular vote expressed at the primaries and caucuses. The new rules will reduce the number of `` super delegates'' _ elected or party leaders _ from 643 to 394, or 15 percent of the delegate total to about 10 percent. Super delegates are not bound by the results of their state contests. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> contended that his super delegate support, which was about one-tenth that of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, did not reflect the popular vote backing he received in some states. The rules also ban direct-election and `` bonus'' primaries, which had the effect of awarding delegates on a `` winner-take-more'' basis. In states such as <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, those systems enabled <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> to amass the delegates needed to clinch the nomination on the last day of the primary season. `` We worked out our differences in a spirit of compromises,'' said <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Vick </PERSON>, vice chairman from <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> and head of the Rules Committee. <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> <PERSON> Barry </PERSON>, mayor of the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> and representative of the <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> forces, said this year `` we worked together ... for a winning team.'' As he left the podium, Ms. <PERSON> Vick </PERSON> said, `` Thank you, Governor <PERSON> Barry </PERSON>,'' a reference to one of the other rule changes. The party will recognize the mayor of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, as a governor in the delegate selection process. The only requirement is that he be a Democrat.
