<SECOND>PM-CVN--Convention Scene,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Entire Hall Is No-Smoking Section As Convention Gets Squeaky-Clean
Start</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT McCARTNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Democratic National Convention opened with a smoking ban, a pledge to stay on time, some homespun politics and a child's view of the presidency. But unity? Not really. Supporters of the Rev. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, some wearing buttons reading `` Respect Blackocrats Or Else,'' waged a war of shouts on the floor of the Omni Monday night. They chanted `` <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON>, Jesse'' each time their candidate's name was mentioned, and audibly overpowered the refrains of `` Duke, <PERSON> Duke </PERSON>. The message was n't lost on the majority of delegates for <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. `` They can have their time,'' said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> supporter <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortiz </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. `` When the whole thing is over, we'll be demonstrating together,'' predicted <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> delegate <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Bielski </PERSON>. `` The party has received their message.'' The party also received a folksy Pledge of Allegiance from radio raconteur and author <PERSON> Garrison </PERSON> <PERSON> Keillor </PERSON> and a group of first graders, as well as celebrity readings of children's essays on the presidency. If that were n't enough wholesomeness, the party banned smoking in the convention hall, driving smokers out to a hazy arena outer lobby. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Agostinelli </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Warwick </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> R.I. </LOCATION>, businessman was on the floor chomping on an unlit cigar. `` I do n't like it, but what are you going to do? I've been a cigar smoker for 35 years. It's tough,'' he said. <PERSON> Agostinelli </PERSON>, a visitor, not a delegate, said, `` I have n't had it lit since I got out of the car, but three people have come up to me and said, ` Would you mind putting that out?''' The Democrats offered everything from b