<HEAD>Carter Regaining Place in Democratic Spotlight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, shunned by his own party after a trying term in the White House that ended in a landslide defeat eight years ago, is edging back toward the spotlight. As his party's only living former president, <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> received a warm reception Monday night after being introduced to the Democrats' national convention as `` a great American and a great Democrat.'' But he barely made prime time, for his appearance was the closing act for the opening night of the Democratic National Convention. Twice he dominated party conventions _ in 1976 when he went on to the presidency and four years later when the campaign ended in humiliating defeat. Delegates applauded for two minutes at the beginning and again at the end of a speech in which he warned the Democrats to set aside their propensity for internal battles. `` If I had to give you just one special message tonight,'' he told them, `` I would summarize it in a single word: unity.'' He urged the delegates to `` go forth from this convention united behind out candidates and our ideals.'' <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> could still remember vividly the 1980 Democratic convention when he was nominated for a second term only after a bitter fight with Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. That convention ended with <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> circling each other on the podium, the senator trying to avoid a peacemaking embrace with his victorious rival. The memory of the 1980 campaign in which Republican <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> carried 44 states to sweep <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> out of office and help propel the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> to control of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> sent <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> into a political exile during which he rarely appeared at party functions. He spoke on the opening night of the 1984 convention, but his appearance was little noticed in the acclaim given the keynote address that year by Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Maxine </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldstein </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Milledgeville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, who was a member of the site selection committee for the 1988 convention, said people would ask when they heard the meeting might be held in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, `` What are you going to do about President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>?'' `` We're going to pull him out and put him on a pedestal and let everyone appreciate him like we appreciate him,'' she said, describing her reply. But the <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> peanut farmer who burst from obscurity in 1976 to win the presidency still had to compete with the keynote speaker _ this time <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> State Treasurer <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Richards </PERSON>. And by the time he spoke, many of the seats that were filled for her speech had emptied. Former Secretary of State <PERSON> Edmund </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Muskie </PERSON> reminded delegates of some of <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>'s finer moments. `` Let us remember him clasping the hands of <PERSON> Anwar </PERSON> <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON> and <PERSON> Menahem </PERSON> <PERSON> Begin </PERSON>,'' said <PERSON> Muskie </PERSON>, recalling the Camp David accords that brought peace between <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. `` He told the truth, he made his country strong,'' added <PERSON> Muskie </PERSON>. Republicans ridiculed <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> for an administration during which Americans were held hostage in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and inflation and interest rates hit double digits. Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> continues to push that image of the <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> years in his campaig