 Doctors at military hospitals will not perform abortions starting Oct. 1 unless the mother's life is in danger. Doctors have been barred since 1979 from performing abortions paid for by the government unless the life of the mother is endangered, but were allowed to perform so-called `` pre-paid abortions'' in `` certain countries in which quality medical care may not be locally available.'' A memo obtained Monday signed by Dr. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayer </PERSON>, assistant <ORGANIZATION> defense </ORGANIZATION> secretary for health affairs, changes the policy. It says `` it might suggest insensitivity to the spirit of the congressionally enacted policy of withholding government involvement in the provision of abortions.'' There were 10,829 abortions performed at military facilities in 1980 and 88 in 1980, after <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> passed the prohibition, according to a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> audit.
