 Each of us pauses on occasion to reassess our own lives: to look at what we have become, the mistakes we've made, and to decide what we would like to be. I think, as a nation, we make this same kind of reassessment when we elect a president. Now is the time to reconsider our opportunities and our challenges _ to make a change _ and to decide what we want for the future. Especially to decide what we want for the future. A democracy is always an unfinished creation. Each generation must rediscover the meaning of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s dream. Tonight I'm thinking not only about the next president, but about our nation's children and how they will live in years to come. <PERSON> Rosalynn </PERSON> and I have six grandchildren. What kind of world will we leave to them and to other young people? In thinking about the past eight years and looking ahead, let's recall the words of a great American president, <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> Listen to what he said: `` Governments can err. Presidents do make mistakes; but ... better the occasional faults of a government that lives in a spirit of charity than the consistent omissions of a government frozen in the ice of its own indifference.'' For the sake of our children, for the sake of our future, we must melt that ice. It's time to reach out for the homeless, to families broken by drug addiction and disease. It's time to clean up those <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> scandals and build a lean, tough, competent military force. It's time to have a <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> that fights for civil rights. It's time to quit living on credit and expecting our children to pay the bills some day. It's time to tackle the continuing problems of poverty, of a decaying environment, of the bankruptcy of family farms. And it's time to invest in the education and care of our children. Because that's the kind of nation we are. That's the kind of people we are. In some ways, <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is a big family. A family does not ignore the sickness or pain of any of its children. A family gives all its members help and love. That is the kind of families we have _ and that's the kind of nation we want. And a good family plans for its children's future _ and that means education. Eight years ago, no American student was deprived of a college education because of financial reasons. But now, for many young Americans, these opportunities have been wiped out. Starting in 1989, that is going to change. We Democrats do not fear change. We welcome it. Because change means hope. Change means life. Above all, change means opportunity. And no changes are more profound than those taking place in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The world is fascinated with the news from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. General Secretary <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has made move after move that would have seemed unthinkable a decade ago.
