<HEAD>President-Elect To Confront A Bundle Of Troubles</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ISAAC A. LEVI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 From triple-digit inflation to a crushing $ 104 billion foreign debt, President-elect <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> faces a series of challenges that would have made some of his 60 predecessors wince. Horrendous unemployment, a ballooning population and growing discontent with the political party that has run <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> since 1929 further threaten to make <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON>' inaugural term something less than a picnic in the park. By the time <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> leaves office in six years, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s population is expected to have grown by about 10 million to 91 million, all crammed in an area three times the size of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Unless he can reverse the trends, that growth will mean more people for fewer jobs. With about half the current population under age 16, it is estimated that by the time <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON>' term ends, about 1 million young people a year will be looking for work for the first time. A recent study by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> showed that only 350,000 jobs were created last year, a drop from the previous year. Another study, by <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON>' <ORGANIZATION> Institutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said roughly 28 percent of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s labor force of 47 million people lack steady jobs and 14 percent are jobless _ a total of 42 percent. Inflation, which reached a 159.2 percent annual rate last year, has eroded the average purchasing power of wages by more than half. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> says one of his priorities will be to restore the value of earnings. `` We will have to provide that and also housing, education, health care and other basic services,'' not only to cut deficits but also for the 6 million new jobseekers who will emerge during his administration, <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> said in a recent interview with the television network <ORGANIZATION> Televisa </ORGANIZATION>. If foreign debt payments become too burdensome they will be renegotiated or suspended altogether, he added. A survey by the governing party think tank _ the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Political </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> _ indicates that gross fixed investment has been dropping by an annual average of nearly 5 percent, with a drop of 12 percent in 1986. For decades, illegal emigration of millions of Mexicans to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> acted as an escape valve for the population problem. But a 1987 law in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> that fines employers who knowingly hire illegal aliens could shut or narrow the aperture. As budget and planning secretary for five years in outgoing President <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Madrid </PERSON>'s administration, <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> was associated with belt-tightening and other unpopular measures. Both the governing party's labor wing and its old guard strongly opposed his nomination. So <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> is now busy trying to mend fences, especially with <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Velazquez </PERSON>, the 88-year-old leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Mexican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION>. The centrist <ORGANIZATION> Institutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, or <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION>, has won every major election since it was founded in 1929, its critics claim it often resorts to ballot fraud. Charges of vote fraud were louder than ever this year as the government delayed release of results until a week after the July 6 balloting, and then said <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> won with just over 50 percent of the vote _ 20 percent less than previous <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> presidential victories. The <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION>'s patronage system still goes deep into the country's grass roots, but its power base has been eroding under pressure from growing forces on both the left and right Many say the party has been unable _ or unwilling _ to meet <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s increasingly greater demands for more orderly government, less corruption, greater economic development and more efficient state services. The disillusionment cuts across social and political lines. People are clamoring against everything from a self-muzzled press to deficient law enforcement to lack of environmental protection to neglect for women's rights. The conservative <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> leftist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> coalition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> have been addressing these issues and picking up votes. For the first time in decades, the governing party's presidential candidate actually had to campaign on the basis of concrete solutions to specific issues, from smog in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> to the drug problem to a growing crime rate <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> acknowledges these challenges, saying reforms and modernization will be the priorities of his administration. He'll begin trying on Dec. 1, the date he officially takes office.
</TEXT>
