<HEAD>Tass Says Rebels Shell Kabul, Kill Eight People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rebels fired rockets into the Afghan capital of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> this morning and one missile blast killed eight people and wounded nine, the Soviet news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. It was the second reported bombardment of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> in five days. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said rockets rained down on city streets and crossroads as people went to work. The only known casualty toll was from the rocket that exploded in the city's <LOCATION> Khairkhan </LOCATION> district, it said. On Friday, 21 rockets were fired into residential areas of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, killing 20 people, wounding 34 and damaging a mosque and other buildings, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported. It blamed the attacks on insurgents fighting the Moscow-backed government of President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>. But <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Haq </PERSON>, a rebel leader in <LOCATION> Peshawar </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, denied that guerrillas target civilian neighborhoods and said the Soviets themselves might have staged the bombardment to sap support for the rebels. The Soviets began withdrawing their more than 100,000 troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> on May 15. Under terms of U.N.-brokered accords, all are to be home by February. Both Afghan and Soviet media have said the guerrillas are stepping up their military activity as the Soviet troops leave.
