<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> warplanes conducted raids along the Iranian coast Tuesday, a day after <ORGANIZATION> Iran </ORGANIZATION> announced it would accept a U.N.-sponsored cease-fire to end the 8-year-old <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> war. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> claimed it shot down an Iranian F-14 in a dogfight and informed sources in the gulf said <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> might also have downed an Iraqi jet fighter. An <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> military spokesman was quoted by <ORGANIZATION> Baghdad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> as saying an <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> warplanes shot down on Iranian warplane over the gulf near the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> port of <LOCATION> Ammiq </LOCATION>. The report, monitored in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, said all Iraqi planes returned safely to base. But gulf sources said an Iranian F-14 had also apparently shot down an Iraqi `` There are a lot of planes in the air,'' said one source, insisting on anonymity. The targets were not immediately identified, he said. It was not known if any of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s tankers or oil terminals were attacked. The official <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, also monitored in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>, said <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> warplanes had violated <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s airspace in southeastern <LOCATION> Khuzestan </LOCATION> province. `` They were intercepted by heavy fire of the Iranian air defense gunners,'' the <ORGANIZATION> IRNA </ORGANIZATION> report said. It did not mention any destruction on the ground, but the agency usually reports bombing as air space violations. The apparent raids were mounted a day after <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> announced it would accept a cease-fire resolution passed by the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> security council on July 20, 1987. The truce would not take effect until details were worked out `` within a week to ten days,'' <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> Secretary General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said on Monday. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has regularly attacked Iranian shuttle tankers and key oil terminals in the gulf in an effort to choke off it's enemy's revenue-earning exports The last two reported Iraqi raids were on July 14. The sources said it was not immediately clear what type of <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> aircraft were involved, but they are usually French-built F-1 Mirages armed with Exocet missiles and other aircraft that carry missiles and boimbs. The Iraqi air activity began about 8 a.m. -LRB- 1 a.m. EDT -RRB- and continued more than two hours later, said one of the sources, who are well informed on shipping activity in the gulf. An Iraqi aircraft was shot down over the central gulf, the sources said, apparently by one of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s U.S.-built F-14 fighters, some of which are known to be based at <LOCATION> Bushehr </LOCATION> on the Iranian coast.
