<HEAD>Canada To Restore Diplomatic Relations With Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> is restoring diplomatic ties with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> that were severed when <ORGANIZATION> Canadian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> officials spirited six American diplomats out of <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> in 1980. The Canadian government said Monday it decided to revive relations after <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> dropped a demand that it apologize for smuggling the Americans out of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. `` There were no conditions. There was no apology,'' a <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> official told a news conference. The official spoke on condition of anonymity. The agreement was reached before <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s announcement Monday that it would accept a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> resolution for a cease-fire in its 8-year-old war with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> closed its embassy in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> after Ambassador <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> sheltered the Americans and then spirited them out of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> during the hostage crisis at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Embassy that began in November 1979. Since 1980, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> maintained diplomatic contact through the <ORGANIZATION> Danish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>, while the Iranian government was represented by a charge d'affaires in <LOCATION> Ottawa </LOCATION>. Under an agreement reached in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> last week, ambassadors will be exchanged and a <ORGANIZATION> Canadian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> reopened by October, officials said. In a formal statement, both governments said restoration of full diplomatic relations `` will lead to increased exchanges in all fields to the mutual benefit of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Islamic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>.'' Foreign Minister <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> said Sunday that moves to improve diplomatic ties did not mean <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> was endorsing the present Iranian government. `` But they are a significant country, significant force in international events and it would be useful we think on the appropriate terms to have normal relations,'' <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> said. He said talks on restoring relations began about a month ago, as <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> resumed normal ties with <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and increased contacts with <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s parliament speaker, <PERSON> Hashemi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, said this month that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> would try to cultivate better international relations. Despite the eight-year diplomatic chill, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> have remained trade partners and exchanged goods worth $ 228 million in 1987, including $ 83 million in Canadian wheat. More than 3,000 Iranians received immigrant visas for <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> in 1987.
