<FIRST>r i PM-China-Inflation     07-19 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Inflation,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prices Jump 19 Percent In Sharpest Climb Since Reforms Began</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Consumer prices jumped 19 percent in the past year, the government announced today, acknowledging the biggest such rise since <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> introduced market reforms a decade ago. <PERSON> Zhang </PERSON> <PERSON> Zhongji </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>, blamed the economy's inability to satisfy consumer demand for the rise. But he said middlemen who hoard goods and control their distribution also are responsible. <PERSON> Zhang </PERSON> also told a news conference that grain production, stagnant for the past two years, is not expected to improve this year. He said workers in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s 32 major cities, including <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wuhan </LOCATION>, were hardest hit by inflation and that food prices increased the most. Prices last month were 19 percent higher than those of June 1987, he said. But Chinese economists do not consider that the country's inflation rate, which they calculate differently than in the West. In <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, the annual inflation rate is calculated by averaging price increases over 12 months rather than measuring the gap between prices from a given date to the same date 12 months later. Using this system, <PERSON> Zhang </PERSON> said consumer prices during the first six months of this year were an average of 13 percent higher than during the first six months of last year. This is what the government considers the inflation rate. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> says inflation was 7.2 percent last year and 11 percent in the first quarter of 1988. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has not previously released an inflation figure calculated by the Western method, as is the 19 percent figure, so this could not be compared against last year. <PERSON> Zhang </PERSON> said food prices during the six-month period were an average of 16.9 percent higher than in the same period last year, and clothing prices were up about 10 percent. Prices in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s 32 major cities were an average of 14.4 percent higher than in the first six months of 1987, but were 19 percent higher in <LOCATION> Canton </LOCATION> and 20 percent higher in <LOCATION> Hefei </LOCATION>. In major cities, <PERSON> Zhang </PERSON> said, wages of one-fifth of the population have failed to keep pace with inflation, leading to a decline in living standards. <PERSON> Zhang </PERSON> did not link the high inflation to the nation's 11 percent economic growth rate during the first half of the year and its 17.2 percent industrial growth rate. Some Chinese economists believe this pace of growth is fueling inflation by creating too high demand for raw materials, transportation and energy. Inflation is one of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s biggest economic problems. Under the reform program introduced in 1978 by senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is moving away from a system where the state sets prices and is allowing the market to determine prices. A two-tier price system has developed, with key items such as grain and pork sold both in state stores at artificially low prices and on the free market at prices set by supply and demand. Prices of many other goods, such as fruit, are completely decontrolled.
</TEXT>
