dropped digits. Picks up 10th graf, `Earlier, in ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar weakened in early European trading today, stung by dollar selling by the West German and Swiss central banks, dealers said. Gold prices were higher. The dollar recovered slightly in late morning trading from opening lows but remained lower against all major currencies compared with Monday's late rates. Sales of dollars by the West German and Swiss central banks in the open market depressed the dollar and unsettled the market, dealers said. `` A lot of traders got their fingers burned, so for the moment the central banks are in charge,'' said a dealer at a major Italian commercial bank in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where the business day ends as <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s begins, the dollar dropped 1.30 Japanese yen to a closing 133.85 yen. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was little changed at 133.88 yen. Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Monday: _ 1.8648 West German marks, down from 1.8823 _ 1.5470 Swiss francs, down from 1.5625 _ 6.2885 French francs, down from 6.3415 _ 2.0995 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1130 _ 1,382.05 Italian lire, down from 1,390.50 _ 1.2055 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2095 In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the British pound rose to $ 1.6867 Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 436.40 a troy ounce, up from $ 436.25 bid late Monday. At midmorning today, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 437.25. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the bid price was $ 437, up from $ 435 bid late Monday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell $ 1.02 to close at a bid $ 438.98. Silver bullion rose in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a bid price of $ 7.15 a troy ounce, up from $ 7.13 bid late Monday.
