<HEAD>Soviets To Inspect U.S. Missile Facilities In Britain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENHAM COMMON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet inspectors today arrived at this air force base to perform the first check on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cruise missiles in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> under the superpower treaty that is to eliminate medium-range nuclear weapons from <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Twenty Soviet inspectors landed at <LOCATION> Greenham </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Common </LOCATION>, 50 miles west of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, early this afternoon aboard an <ORGANIZATION> Aeroflot </ORGANIZATION> jet. The Soviets were welcomed by a delegation of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and British officers. The inspection visit is one of the terms of the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty signed in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> on Dec. 8 by Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. The treaty provides for the elimination within three years of all nuclear missiles with ranges of 340 miles to 3,000 miles and includes stringent inspection provisions to guard against cheating. <LOCATION> Greenham </LOCATION> Common is one of two <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cruise missile bases in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. The other is at <LOCATION> Molesworth </LOCATION>, 50 miles north of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. Both bases are run by <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> personnel, but are technically <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> bases. <LOCATION> Greenham </LOCATION> Common has 96 operational missiles and five back-up missiles, while there are another 16 operational missiles at <LOCATION> Molesworth </LOCATION>, according to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military. At <LOCATION> Greenham </LOCATION> Common, a customs and immigration post was set up to receive the Soviets and check the cameras, geiger counters and other equipment they were allowed to bring for the inspection. They are to stay overnight in converted servicemen's accommodations at <LOCATION> Greenham </LOCATION> Common, and are to eat meals at a cafeteria on the base Under the treaty, the inspectors may check the missiles and their mobile launchers _ which are to be taken back to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and destroyed _ but not the warheads. At the bases, the Soviets may also place security men at all entry and exit roads to ensure no missiles are surreptitiously moved out, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said. `` We're entirely in the Soviets' hands,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>. `` They will say where they want to go.'' The inspectors, who will be flown to <LOCATION> Molesworth </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Greenham </LOCATION> Common, will not be allowed to step outside the bases during their stay, which is expected to last up to 4 -LCB- days, or until the inspection is completed. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officers, mostly from an on-site inspection agency based in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, will accompany the Soviets as they examine the missiles and launchers. Soviet inspectors first checked missiles in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> on July 1 at two West German sites housing Pershing-2 rockets. The current inspections are part of a 60-day period of `` baseline inspections'' to determine the accuracy of data exchanged by the two sides. The Soviets are visiting 30 sites in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> while <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> inspectors are visiting 133 Soviet sites. So far, no violations have been discovered, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials say, and the inspections are about 25 percent complete. The Soviets notified the British of their visit on Monday, officials said, under the 16-hour notice-of-inspection rule. In November 1983, <ORGANIZATION> Greenham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Common </ORGANIZATION> was the first Western European base to accept <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cruise missiles under a December 1979 <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> alliance accord.
