<HEAD>NYC To Lower Estimate Of Number Of Residents Infected With HIV</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 City health officials have lowered their estimate of the number of New Yorkers infected with the AIDS virus by nearly half, to 250,000, according to a report published today. The new estimate is based mainly on a reduction in the estimated population of homosexual and bisexual men living in the city, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported. The new estimates were to be presented tonight to a panel headed by Health Commissioner <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON>. The Times attributed the 250,000 estimate to an epidemiologist who worked on the figures. The previous estimated number of infected New Yorkers was 400,000, or one in every 18 city residents. Then-Health Commissioner <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Sencer </PERSON> released that figure in 1985 and called it `` conservative.'' In the earlier projections, health officials estimated there were half a million gay and bisexual men in the city, with 60 percent believed to be infected. The new estimate is expected to be cut roughly in half, with the percentage infected to remain the same, the Times said. The number of infected intravenous drug users, who now account for more new cases in the city than any other group, is not expected to change. There is no known cure for acquired immune deficiency syndrome, which is caused by a virus that attacks the body's immune system. <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Sweeney </PERSON>, deputy director of the Gay Men's Health Crisis, told the Times he believes the figures undercount the gay population. `` Everybody knows that big cities, and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in particular, act as a magnet and that there has been a great migration of gays,'' he said.
