cease-fire called. Picks up 4th graf pvs ``The attacks ....''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Moslem Shiite tribesmen bombarded a <ORGANIZATION> Maronite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> town with rockets, howitzers and mortars for a third day today. Police said five people were killed and 25 wounded. The flighting raised the casualty toll to 11 dead and 45 wounded since clashes began Sunday between members of the <ORGANIZATION> Jaafar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> clan and other residents of the Syrian-policed town of <LOCATION> Qoubaiyat </LOCATION>, 70 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. A police spokesman in <LOCATION> Tripoli </LOCATION>, the provincial capital of north <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, said residents of <LOCATION> Qoubaiyat </LOCATION> early today repulsed three major attacks by about 2,000 members of the <PERSON> Jaafar </PERSON> clan. A cease-fire was called for 2 p.m., and police said the fighting abated after that time. The attacks were preceded by a fierce barrage from rocket launchers, howitzers and mortars, with shells slamming into <PERSON> Qoubaiyat </PERSON> at the rate of about 10 rounds per minute, added the spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity. He said several mortar rounds fell into the courtyard of the town's ancient stone church, causing some damage. The church houses six monks and 20 nuns, who were unhurt, he added. The spokesman said the clashes began Sunday, a day after armed shepherds from Qoubaiyat and the Jaafars engaged in a brief firefight over grazing rights in sheep pastures on the town's western edge `` Two people were killed in the original clash for pastures. But it seems the incident has developed into a Shiite-Maronite war,'' the spokesman said. He spoke on condition of anonymity. The residents of <PERSON> Qoubaiyat </PERSON> appealed to Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> for `` immediate intervention to stop the military offensive against our peaceful town.'' The ap