<HEAD>Soviets Said Ready To Scrap Krasnoyarsk Radar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chief of Soviet arms negotiations said today the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> will scrap a radar station the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> claims violates the anti-ballistic missile treaty if <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> commits itself to the pact for at least 10 years. However, <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'s disarmament section, repeated the <ORGANIZATION> Kremlin </ORGANIZATION>'s contention that the <LOCATION> Krasnoyarsk </LOCATION> radar station in <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION> is `` aimed at monitoring space objects'' and is thus not covered by the 1972 treaty The pact restricts both superpowers' defenses against nuclear missiles. Some advisers to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> are said to be recommending that he accuse the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> of committing a `` material breach'' of the treaty by operating the phrased-array radar station. They reportedly want him to abrogate the pact. Other <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> advisers have suggested <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> try to persuade the Soviets to level the facility in the interest of preserving the ABM treaty. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, a phrased-array radar is able to track many object accurately, meaning it could detect ballistic missiles and could potentially contribute to ABM battle management. <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON> told a news briefing that construction work at the radar station has been stopped as a sign of `` good will.'' `` This moratorium is still in force,'' said the diplomat, who once headed the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> negotiating team at the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> arms talks. Superpower representatives are now negotiating a 50 percent cut in strategic nuclear weapons. <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON> said Soviet envoys were seeking an agreement that would commit the superpowers to observing the ABM treaty for at least 10 years. He called that commitment `` the necessary element'' for reaching an accord on halving superpower strategic arsenals. `` In this framework we are prepared also for a radical solution to the <LOCATION> Krasnoyarsk </LOCATION> radar issue raised by the Americans,'' <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON> said. `` If an understanding to abide by the ABM treaty, as signed in 1972, is reached, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> will be ready to dismantle the <LOCATION> Krasnoyarsk </LOCATION> radar in a verifiable way that would leave no doubts on the part of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' he said. The ABM treaty limits how fast and far the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> can go in its search for a space-based defense against ballistic missiles. The so-called `` Star Wars'' program is being carried out under what the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration describes as a `` strict interpretation'' of the treaty. A broader interpretation would provide more leeway, and scrapping the treaty would remove all legal restraints on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> program, which the Soviets oppose as a new and dangerous turn in the superpower arms race.
