<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Protesters bombed railroad tracks and halted a train carrying 1,200 workers to jobs today, <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> police said, as a communist-led labor federation began a two-day national strike against government economic policy. Strikers in the capital blocked key highways with burning garbage and leftist guerrillas sparked a blackout in the highlands, but there were no early reports of violent clashes between police and strikers, officials said. Police said a train carrying workers to their jobs in <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Chosica </LOCATION>, 25 miles to the east, was halted midway when saboteurs blew up a small section of track. The train stopped before reaching the damaged track and there were no injuries. The 48-hour strike was called by the General Confederation of Peruvian Workers to protest government-approved increases of between 20 and 100 percent for food prices. They also protested rising inflation, expected to hit 400 percent this year. The organization, which claims more than 1.5 million members, said two-thirds of the nation's seven million workers were joining the two-day walkout. The strike, the third against President <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>, was declared illegal by the government. Dozens of armed police were deployed on transit buses to ensure that workers reach their jobs. Traffic in <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> flowed smoothly but was lighter than normal with fewer buses on the streets. A spokesman at the capital's international airport said flights were normal. Maoist guerrillas blew up power pylons and caused a blackout in <LOCATION> Ayacucho </LOCATION>, 225 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>, as the strike there paralyzed most business activity, police said. Radio Programas, <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s leading news station, reported the strike slowed commercial activity in the provincial capitals of <LOCATION> Huancayo </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Arequipa </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Puno </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Cuzco </LOCATION>. There were no serious reports of violence in <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> early today, but reporters said police fired tear gas to drive off small pockets of protesters who attempted to block key arteries into the capital with burning garbage. The nation's largest mine workers federation began an indefinite strike Monday, which has slowed or halted most mine operations across the country, strike officials said. It was still unclear in the capital today how effective the strike was in closing factories and halting economic activity. On Monday, police said leftist guerrillas exploded a car bomb in front of the military's joint command headquarters in <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>, wounding three people. Police said a student protester was shot dead during a demonstration at <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marcos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> medical school Monday but circumstances surrounding the death were unclear.
