<HEAD>Sandinistas Mark Ninth Anniversary of Revolution Triumph</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs on Ortega's speech. Picks up x graf pvs
``The anniversary....''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>, speaking at the ninth anniversary of his leftist government, said today that <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> has been socialist since 1979. `` There were expectations on this July 19 that we were going to declare outselves socialists,'' the president, wearing a plaid cowboy shirt, said in the nationally broadcast speech. `` They have n't understood yet that we are socialists, and there's socialism in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> since 1979. It was believed to be the first time that he or any of the <LOCATION> Sandininista </LOCATION> leaders described themselves as socialists. Recently Sandinista leaders have said that the country had a mixed economy with socialist orientation. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> spoke to a crowded stadium in the central city of <LOCATION> Juigalpa </LOCATION>, 85 miles east of the capital. He also urged the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to renew bilateral talks, last held in 1984, to normalize relations. The president called on the U.S.-backed rebels, known as Contras, to reopen stalled discussions on a definitive cease-fire. He also said government troops would extend a truce until Aug. 30. The current cease-fire was due to expire at the end of this month. The anniversary marks the day <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas arrived triumphantly in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>, the capital, after a 1 -LCB- - year civil war that ended four decades of dictatorial rule by the Somoza dynasty Troops on Monday conducted searches at roadblocks along the road to the site of the festivities in <LOCATION> Juigalpa </LOCATION>, 85 miles east of <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>. Also, the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> banned alcohol sales for 24 hours in <LOCATION> Chontales </LOCATION> province, where anniversary festivities also are being held. The measures followed three days of military exercises that ended Sunday. The armed forces, using tanks, helicopters and guns, joined civilians to act out air strikes and land attacks. Also Sunday, thousands of youths attended dances to celebrate the `` Day of Happiness,'' marking the day in 1979 when President <PERSON> Anastasio </PERSON> <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON> left the country. The celebrations come as a quick and permanent end to the government's 7-year war with the Contras remains elusive. Negotiations broke down in June for a lasting peace to the conflict that has claimed 26,000 lives. The rebels in recent weeks have staged almost daily ambushes despite a cease-fire agreement signed March 23. The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said Monday five rebels had been killed in two attacks on troop positions. The statement said rebels kidnapped 10 civilians Friday and Saturday. The government last week expelled <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Melton </PERSON> and seven other American diplomats. It accused the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Embassy of being behind a plan to incite domestic unrest. Also last week, courts sentenced to six months in jail three dozen opposition figures who attended an anti-government demonstration that police broke up with tear gas and beatings. The <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> also shut down the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> radio station and a private news show and suspended the only opposition newspaper, <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION>, for 15 days. Citing economic reasons, the government nationalized the largest private enterprise, the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION> sugar refinery. Lawmakers in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> are discussing resuming military aid to the Contras, which <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> cut off in February in hopes the Sandinistas would deliver on promises of democratic reforms. The government claims most of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s problems center on the war with the Contras, which it says has caused $ 3.6 billion in damage to the economy. The threat of renewed fighting means thousands of displaced people can not return home in north and central regions. Meanwhile, the unpopular military draft continues. The war has stifled promises of social programs. Scores of schools and clinics built after 1979 have been destroyed. The country's more than 3 million people suffer shortages of rice, beans, water and gasoline. Most of the blame has been placed on the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which financed the Contras, cut off economic aid in 1981 and established a trade embargo in 1985. But the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> express pride in having survived to their ninth anniversary without the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> invasion they have always said they expect. On Monday, a cartoon in the Sandinista newspaper Barricada depicted a baseball game, the nation's most popular sport, between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. It showed a score board noting 9-0 and a disheveled Uncle <PERSON> Sam </PERSON>.
