<HEAD>Shiites And Catholics Clash In North Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Maronite Catholics in north <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> on Tuesday repulsed fierce attacks on their town by Shiite Moslem gunmen, and police said five people were killed and 25 wounded in the fighting. The attacks raised the casualty toll to 11 dead and 45 wounded since fighting began Sunday between the <PERSON> Shiite </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaafar </PERSON> clan and residents of the Catholic town of <LOCATION> Qoubaiyat </LOCATION>, 70 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. A police spokesman in <LOCATION> Tripoli </LOCATION>, the provincial capital of north <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, said residents of Qoubaiyat repulsed three attacks Tuesday by 2,000 Jaafars before a cease-fire was called. He said the Jaafars launched the attacks with a fierce barrage from rocket launchers, howitzers and mortars. The shells slammed into Qoubaiyat at the intensity of 10 rounds per minute at one point, the spokesman said. He said several mortar rounds fell into the courtyard of Qoubaiyat's ancient stone church, causing some damage. But the six monks and 20 nuns sheltered there were not hurt. The <PERSON> Jaafar </PERSON> clan, estimated at 35,000 people, is based in the central <LOCATION> Bekaa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> on the western edge of the <LOCATION> Akkar </LOCATION> plateau, a region traditionally dominated by Maronite Catholics and Sunni Moslems. <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, the main power broker in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, maintains 25,000 troops in the <LOCATION> Bekaa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> and north <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> under a 1976 peacekeeping mandate from the 21-nation <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>. The spokesman, who requested anonymity, said Brig. Gen. <PERSON> Ghazi </PERSON> <PERSON> Kenaan </PERSON>, chief of the Syrian army's military intelligence in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, drove to Qoubaiyat shortly after midday to supervise implementation of the cease-fire. The Syrian army is to control `` a buffer zone separating Qoubaiyat's fighters from the Jaafars,'' the spokesman said. He said the clashes started Sunday, one day after armed shepherds from Qoubaiyat and the Jaafars engaged in a brief firefight over sheep grazing terrain in the hamlet of <LOCATION> Shanbook </LOCATION>, on the town's western edge. `` Two people were killed in the original fight for pastures. But it seems the incident has developed into a Shiite-Maronite war,'' the spokesman added. Tuesday's attack on Qoubaiyat shattered a Syrian-sponsored cease-fire declared on Monday. Qoubaiyat, population 25,000, is the fourth largest Catholic town in north <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. About one-fourth of <PERSON> Qoubaiyat </PERSON>'s residents serve in the Lebanese army.
