<HEAD>Lobbying Probe Hits Wisconsin's Clean Image</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 16th graf, `Wisconsin hasn't...,' to CORRECT to
secretary of state sted attorney general.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD EGGLESTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>'s squeaky-clean image has been shaken by accusations that a top <PERSON> Madison </PERSON> lobbyist bought meals for legislators and paid for travel in a possible violation of state law. Some legislators and others say the the infractions are minor _ one of the meals cost $ 5 or $ 6 _ especially when compared to states with a greater history of government scandal. But the state director of <ORGANIZATION> Common </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cause </ORGANIZATION>, the self-styled citizen lobbying group, said <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> should judge itself by its own standards, not by those of states where such infractions would barely leave a ripple. By <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> standards, he said, `` we've got some problems here.'' <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>'s lobbying law, believed to be tougher than most, prohibits public officials from accepting anything of value from lobbyists, except limited campaign contributions after June 1 of election years. Common Cause is pushing for an even tougher law. Lobbyist <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Goyke </PERSON>, a former state senator, filed lawsuits last week in a so-far unsuccessful attempt to stop <ORGANIZATION> Milwaukee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Magazine </ORGANIZATION> from publishing an article about his lobbying practices that he contends were based on office files taken by a former employee. The article is to appear late this month in August editions. <PERSON> Goyke </PERSON> also asked for a state investigation into his activities, predicting it would show he had violated no laws. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney's office disclosed it already was investigating. And state Attorney General <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanaway </PERSON> said Tuesday he would launch an investigation, after Secretary of <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Follette </ORGANIZATION