<HEAD>Soviets Offer to Scrap Krasnoyarsk Radar</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to CORRECT to ``phased array'' sted
``phrased array.'' Pickup 6th graf pvs, ``Karpov, who...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> offered Tuesday to scrap a radar station the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> says is in violation of the anti-ballistic missile treaty if <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> will honor the 1972 pact for at least 10 more years. <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> disarmament section, also repeated the Kremlin contention that the <LOCATION> Krasnoyarsk </LOCATION> radar station in <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION> is `` aimed at monitoring space objects'' and thus outside the ABM treaty, which restricts superpower defenses against nuclear missiles. Some advisers to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> are said to recommend that he accuse the Soviets of making a `` material breach'' of the treaty with the phased-array radar station and abrogate the agreement. Other advisers have suggested <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> try to persuade the Soviets to raze the facility in the interest of preserving the ABM accord. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, a phased-array radar is able to track many objects accurately, meaning it could detect ballistic missiles and contribute to ABM battle management. <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON>, who is in charge of Soviet arms negotiations, told a news briefing that construction work at the radar station has been stopped as a sign of `` good will.'' `` This moratorium is still in force,'' he said. <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON> once led the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> delegation to U.S.-Soviet nuclear arms talks in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, where negotiators now are discussing a 50 percent cut in strategic nuclear weapons. He said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> wants an arrangement that would commit the superpowers to the ABM treaty for at least 10 years, describing that as `` the necessary element'' for such an agreement on long-range nuclear arms. `` In this framework we are prepared also for a radical solution to the <LOCATION> Krasnoyarsk </LOCATION> radar issue raised by the Americans,'' he said. `` If an understanding to abide by the ABM treaty, as signed in 1972, is reached, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> will be ready to dismantle the <LOCATION> Krasnoyarsk </LOCATION> radar in a verifiable way that would leave no doubts on the part of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' The ABM treaty limits how fast and far the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> can go in its plan for a space-based defense against ballistic missiles. The Strategic Defense Initiative, commonly called `` Star Wars,'' is being carried out under what the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration calls a `` strict interpretation'' of the treaty. Broader interpretation would provide more leeway and scrapping the agreement would remove all legal restraints on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> program, which the Soviets say represents a new and dangerous stage of the arms race.
