<HEAD>Second Deathy Penalty Imposed In `Trailside Slayings'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man convicted in the `` Trailside Slayings'' was sentenced to death for the second time Tuesday for murdering five hikers in 1980. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carpenter </PERSON>, 58, of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, had already been sentenced to death for murdering two women in 1981 in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cruz </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> state parks. Superior Court Judge <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> on Tuesday imposed the sentence recommended June 27 by the jury that convicted <PERSON> Carpenter </PERSON> of first-degree murder. <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> could have sentenced <PERSON> Carpenter </PERSON> to life in prison without parole. He refused to do so, however, after recounting <PERSON> Carpenter </PERSON>'s criminal history since 1960, which involves at least eight violent attacks on women `` Mr. <PERSON> Carpenter </PERSON> is, without question, a serial killer ... and a habitual criminal likely to commit violent acts against others,'' <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> said. `` Two previous periods of incarceration, from 1960-69 and 1970-79, had no effect on his criminal activity.'' All appeals in capital cases go directly to the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Marin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defender </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Frank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cox </ORGANIZATION> had asked that <PERSON> Carpenter </PERSON>'s life be spared, arguing that he committed the crimes during moments of rage arising from a lifetime of abuse and rejection. Deputy District Attorney <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Posey </PERSON> contended that <PERSON> Carpenter </PERSON> shot the hikers execution-style after his sexual advances were rejected, and said <PERSON> Carpenter </PERSON> deserved to die for th