<HEAD>Farmers Get Help from Nature; Hope for More from Washington</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON>, beginning a 10-state inspection of drought damage, met Tuesday with farmers in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> who got some relief from nature but are hoping for more from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. As much as 2 -LCB- inches of rain fell in the two states on Monday and Tuesday. But at <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON>'s first stop, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Scherer </PERSON>'s farm near <LOCATION> Shelby </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, the cornfields were still bone dry only a half-inch below the surface. In <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> said his department has received all the crop data required to assess requests for disaster declarations, but gave no indication what assistance would be offered. `` I do n't think it will take very long for us to do an evaluation,'' he said at Avery Sheets' farm near <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lafayette </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind </LOCATION>. `` I would say in days rather than weeks or months.'' At best, Sheets said, he may harvest 30 percent of a normal crop from the 1,000 acres he planted in corn. `` It might be just all cob and no kernels,'' he said, showing an ear to <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON>. While the agriculture secretary expressed concern about the plight of farmers, whose crops have withered under 100-degree temperatures and a months-long rainfall shortage, several of the farmers said interest and aid might be too late. <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> `` came knowing there were n't any answers,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Rieman </PERSON>, a farmer from <LOCATION> Crestline </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> said he anticipated heavier losses than the national average. `` This has always been a reliable production area,'' <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> said, and that might account for the