<HEAD>USDA Says Seed Corn Won't Be Counted As Feed Grain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Growers of hybrid corn for seed will have the option of planting their crop and not have it counted as a feed grain under 1988 acreage programs, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. Acting Undersecretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> said the hybrid seed corn may not be grown on acreage taken from production under 1988 programs or on land enrolled in the long-term Conservation Reserve Program. Further, the additional acreage used to produce seed will not be counted when establishing base acreages for future feed grain crops, he said. Farmers who decided to use this option will not be eligible for 1988 feed grain program benefits on the acres used for the seed crop. <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> said the action was taken to help offset the effects of drought on seed farms and to ensure that farmers will have enough seed for 1989 plantings. The option is expected to be used primarily in southern areas where the growing season is longer. Interested producers can check with local offices of the <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stabilization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> for further details, he said.
