<HEAD>Government Says Security at Stake in Voice of America Article</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The federal government contended Tuesday that foreign policy and national security interests require a <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> employee who wrote an article critical of the agency to submit the article to a censor before publication. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Dempster </PERSON>, an assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney, told a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> judge that the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s pre-publication regulations are designed to help keep employees from violating the law. `` Substantial foreign policy and national security interests support the pre-publication regulations,'' he told the court. `` Such activity -LRB- writing an unauthorized article -RRB- could jeopardize security, disrupt foreign relations and impair the mission of the agency.'' At issue in the case is an article written by <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> employee <PERSON> Carolyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Weaver </PERSON> that is scheduled to appear in the September-October issue of the <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journalism </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Review </ORGANIZATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Weaver </PERSON> said in an affidavit that the article details political abuses by the <ORGANIZATION> VOA </ORGANIZATION>, including `` the apparent illegal use of <ORGANIZATION> VOA </ORGANIZATION> programs for covert activity.'' Ms. <PERSON> Weaver </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohn </PERSON>, told the court that the regulation `` is too broad ... goes too far.'' `` Ms. <PERSON> Weaver </PERSON> is a part-time worker ... a script writer ... for the <ORGANIZATION> VOA </ORGANIZATION>. She does n't deal with secrets.'' he said. `` What they -LRB- the government -RRB- want to do is take regulations that cover the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-, expand the coverage and apply them to all employees who work in anything to do with foreign policy.'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Penfield </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> took the case under advisement. He said, however, he could not guarantee he would make a decision on issuing a preliminary injunction declaring the regulations unconstitutional in time for Ms. <PERSON> Weaver </PERSON> to make her deadline of July 20 with the <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journalism </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Review </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Kohn </PERSON> said afterward that if <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> rules against Ms. <PERSON> Weaver </PERSON>, he would seek an expedited review before the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Weaver </PERSON> challenged the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> rules after she was ordered to submit the article to a censor. Under <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> regulations that also apply to the <ORGANIZATION> VOA </ORGANIZATION>, employees of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> are required to submit their writings, speeches or teaching materials `` on matters of official concern'' for clearance prior to pub