<HEAD>Skyscraper Blaze Blamed On Refinishing Chemicals</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS graf 5, `The flames...' with 2 grafs to update with
report of injury to one worker and update damage estimate to
$500,000; picks up graf 6, `Officials said...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vapors from chemicals being used in a furniture refinishing project caused the fire that gutted two office suites in the 38-story <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> building, fire officials said Tuesday. `` It was accidental,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wells </PERSON>. `` Chemical vapors made contact with an electrical outlet,'' causing a flash fire. Monday night's blaze was a haunting reminder of the May 4 fire that killed one man and ravaged five floors of the city's tallest building, the 62-story <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> building. There were no deaths in the <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> fire, but two of the 150 firefighters called to battle flames on the 34th and 35th floors were treated by paramedics for exhaustion and heat. A worker who was refinishing a bookcase on the 34th floor sustained minor burns, said Fire Chief <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Manning </PERSON>. The flames destroyed two office suites and caused slight damage to the surrounding area, causing $ 500,000 damage, officials said. Officials said lessons learned in fighting the earlier fire helped fight Monday night's blaze, even though the <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> building, like <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION>, has no fire extinguishers. <PERSON> Manning </PERSON> said the fire was put out in less than 45 minutes because the alarm was sounded quickly. Also, water was available and better communications were set up. In the First Interstate fire, radios between fire floors and command officials outside failed to work, but new, more powerful radios prevented a communication problem Monday night. The <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> blaze gave new impetus to the move to hasten implementation of a law requiring sprinklers in high-rises. The Union Bank tower was built in 1966, prior to the 1974 city ordinance requiring sprinklers. Last Friday, the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> voted to mandate sprinklers within four years in 343 pre-1974 high-rises, and sprinklers were actually in the process of being installed at <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. `` It is unconscionable to build high-rises without sprinklers in them,'' Councilman <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Braude </PERSON> said after the Monday blaze. Councilman <PERSON> Nate </PERSON> <PERSON> Holden </PERSON> agreed, saying `` dragging our feet has already caused two major fires in <LOCATION> L.A. </LOCATION>'' Eighty-three people in the <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> building escaped down stairwells. Most tenants were back inside on Tuesday and operations were described as normal by bank officials. `` I was jumping three steps at a time,'' said <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> <PERSON> Franks </PERSON>, an asbestos removal worker who was on the 28th floor when he heard an evacuation call over the building intercom. `` A few people were following and some stumbled and fell. I was on the 16th floor when I saw firefighters coming up the stairs.'' Firefighters lugged hoses and others carried equipment weighing up to 100 pounds up 34 flights of stairs. At midnight, the building changed ownership: <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> tower became property of <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, which acquired <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in a $ 750 million transaction.
