<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENHAM COMMON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Soviet official said on Tuesday that inspections in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> show a superpower treaty scrapping intermediate-range nuclear missiles is being implemented without cheating. <PERSON> Vyacheslav </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lebedev </PERSON> made the remark after he and 19 other Soviet inspectors landed at this air force base to start counting <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cruise missiles in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> in accordance with the treaty. The Soviet inspectors arrived at <LOCATION> Greenham </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Common </LOCATION>, 50 miles west of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, aboard a blue-and-white <ORGANIZATION> Aeroflot </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ilyushin </ORGANIZATION> jet. They were welcomed by a delegation of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and British officers. <LOCATION> Greenham </LOCATION> Common is one of two <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cruise missile bases in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. The other is at <LOCATION> Molesworth </LOCATION>, 50 miles north of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. Both bases are run by <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> personnel, but are technically <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> bases. The base has 96 operational missiles and five back-up missiles, while there are another 16 operational missiles at <LOCATION> Molesworth </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military says. <PERSON> Lebedev </PERSON> said that, based on similar inspections this month in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, no one seemed to be cheating on the terms of the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty signed in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on Dec. 8 by Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. `` The experience of the inspections has shown that the <ORGANIZATION> U.S.S.R. </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> strictly implemented the treaty signed by them and the first steps as to its realization are successful,'' said <PERSON> Lebedev </PERSON>. Soviet inspectors arrived in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> July 16 to inspect some of the 14 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> missile sites, training facilities and industrial plants. These include <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sill </LOCATION> in southwestern <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, which has 37 <ORGANIZATION> Pershing </ORGANIZATION> 2 missiles and <ORGANIZATION> Redstone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arsenal </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Huntsville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, home of the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Missile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> that manages the Pershing 1A and <ORGANIZATION> Pershing </ORGANIZATION> 2 nuclear missile programs. The treaty provides for the elimination within three years of all nuclear missiles with ranges of 340 miles to 3,000 miles and includes stringent inspection provisions to guard against cheating. At <LOCATION> Greenham </LOCATION> Common, a customs and immigration post was set up to receive the Soviets and check the cameras, <PERSON> Geiger </PERSON> counters and other equipment they were allowed to bring for the inspection. They are to stay at the base overnight in converted servicemen's accommodations, and are to eat meals at a cafeteria on the base Under the treaty, the inspectors may check the missiles and their 55-foot mobile launchers _ which are to be taken back to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and destroyed _ but not the warheads. The Soviets were to declare Wednesday exactly what they want to see at the bases. They may also place security men at all entry and exit roads to ensure no missiles are surreptitiously moved out, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said. `` We're entirely in the Soviets' hands,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>. `` They will say where they want to go.'' The inspectors, who will be flown to <LOCATION> Molesworth </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Greenham </LOCATION> Common, will not be allowed to step outside the bases during their stay, which is expected to last up to 4 -LCB- days, or until the inspection is completed. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officers, mostly from an on-site inspection agency based in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, will accompany the Soviets as they examine the missiles and launchers. Soviet inspectors first checked missiles in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> on July 1 at two West German sites housing Pershing-2 rockets. The current inspections are part of a 60-day period of `` baseline inspections'' to determine the accuracy of data exchanged by the two sides. The Soviets are visiting 30 sites in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> while <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> inspectors are visiting 133 Soviet sites. So far, no violations have been discovered, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials say, and the inspections are about 25 percent complete. The Soviets notified the British of their visit on Monday, officials said, under the 16-hour notice-of-inspection rule. In November 1983, <ORGANIZATION> Greenham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Common </ORGANIZATION> was the first Western European base to accept <LOCATION> U.S.