<HEAD>Disappearing News Conferences, Demonstrations Mark Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Call it the case of the mystery press conference. A group of Democratic senators and congressmen scheduled a 1:30 p.m. press conference Tuesday to talk about the independent prosecutor's report on Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>. The event was listed on the Democratic convention's daily calendar. Came 1:30, a handful of reporters was there. But not the senators or congressmen. A party spokesman said the event had been moved to a nearby hotel where Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON>, D-Mass., was to attend an unrelated session on fighting drugs The two events had been merged, the spokesman said. But <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Carpman </PERSON>, <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON>'s spokesman, said his boss was not involved. Try the office of Sen. <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, D-Mich., a long-time critic of <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s behavior in government <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>'s people said they had nothing to do with the event. `` This thing's not going to happen,'' said a party spokesman. He was right.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Speaking of Events that Never Were: People with AIDS Coalition, a newly formed AIDS prevention group in <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, had obtained a permit for a 90-minute program in the `` protest zone,'' an empty parking lot about a block from the convention hall. Again, reporters showed up, but none of the advocates. No one there knew why. `` We've had several groups that did n't show up,'' said Lt. W.F. <PERSON> Derrick </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> police department.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Scaling the Heights: He has the votes to be the Democratic nominee for president, but does <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> have the stature to fill the office? Sure. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, at 5-foot-8, is not another <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON> -LRB- 6-foot-4 -RRB- but he's as tall or taller than nine <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> presidents including the <ORGANIZATION> Adamses </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Quincy </PERSON>, both 5-foot-7. That has n't prevented the occasional jibe, one of which was repeated on air Monday by <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> anchorman <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON>. He quoted an unidentified senior aide to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>: `` We want a convention that is organized, orderly and short _ just like our candidate.'' If elected, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> would be the shortest president since <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> McKinley </PERSON> -LRB- 5-foot-7 -RRB- won office in 1896. The shortest was 5-foot-4.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Smelling the fumes: <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s `` Rainbow Express'' bus caravan rolled through five states en route to <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> in airconditioned comfort. But once in the convention city, the means of transport changed to dilapidated, non-airconditioned school buses. Two of them carried the <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> press corps to a luncheon given by former President <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>. One broke down as it wheezed up the Carter Center driveway. That meant squeezing the hot reporters, crews and cameras into just one steamy bus for the trip back. It was too much for the bus. It stopped dead on a slight grade but was revived to pick up the reporters who decided the better part of valor was to walk. The rest of the journey was inch-by-inch, keeping fingers crossed. For reporters it gave new meaning to the <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> battle cry: `` Keep hope alive.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Michelangelo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Painted </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ceilings </ORGANIZATION>, Did n't He? You can hardly go anywhere in this town without bumping into reporters, a species identified by a `` where-do-I-get-a-story'' look that's unmistakable. But there's danger of stepping on others in the public arts, too. Outside the Hyatt Regency Hotel, which is <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' headquarters, <PERSON> Sidewalk </PERSON> <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> _ also known as <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Guillemin </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> _ is doing his thing His thing being painting chalk portraits on sidewalks. Big portraits. The likeness he's doing now? Who else but the <PERSON> Duke </PERSON>?
