<HEAD>Grand Jury Begins Taking Testimony In Pentagon Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: TOPS with 3 grafs with Unisys shakeup, picks up 2nd graf pvs,
Meanwhile, an; ADDS 10 grafs on Unisys actions</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal grand jury began hearing witnesses on Tuesday in the massive Pentagon bribery investigation, while a major contractor fired all its defense-contract consultants and shook up the management of one division. <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, whose offices on <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, have been searched by federal agents, announced that its own, independent investigation begun last fall by former Watergate special prosecutor <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> had uncovered activity contrary to company policy. <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Blumenthal </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> secretary, placed a <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> division under new management, put some employees on administrative leave and terminated `` all consulting contracts with those who represented the company before the federal government on defense-related matters.'' Meanwhile, an attorney for defense consultant and former <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> official <PERSON> Melvyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Paisley </PERSON> filed motions to quash 11 subpoenas from the grand jury and to be advised if the government conducted any illegal electronic surveillance of his client. In all, 275 subpoenas, mostly for documents and records, were due to be answered in <LOCATION> Alexandria </LOCATION> on Tuesday. <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> <PERSON> Dibbley </PERSON>, spokeswoman for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON>, said the government had arranged a location, which she would not identify, where lawyers and those under subpoena could deliver records without being observed by reporters. Many of the subpoenas are to persons who are only potential witnesses in the investigation and not targets of it. Ms. <