<HEAD>Milk Output Expected About 1 Percent Above Last Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Milk production may not increase this year as much as forecast earlier, an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report said Tuesday. `` For all of 1988, milk production probably will total about 1 percent more than 1987's 142.5 billion pounds,'' the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said Earlier, the agency said the increase could be in the range of 1 percent to 3 percent. `` Downward pressure on milk production will intensify during the second half of 1988,'' the report said. `` Concentrate -LRB- grain -RRB- prices will be much higher, and forage costs will rise sharply in areas hit by the drought.'' Seasonal increases in milk prices will `` likely be larger'' than last year, although the average price at the farm for all of 1988 probably will be down 3 percent to 5 percent from last year's $ 12.54 per 100 pounds, the report said `` May retail prices were less than 2 percent higher than a year ago, and only half the increase for all food or all consumer items,'' the report said. `` Seasonal upswings in retail prices may be slightly larger than a year earlier during the second half of 1988. However, retail dairy prices probably will average only 1 percent to 3 percent higher for the year.''
