<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN WOLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The most precious commodity in a political campaign _ more than money or endorsements or straw hats with red, white and blue bunting _ is what insiders refer to as `` the body.'' This week, the body belongs to one <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. To see what the Democrats want to achieve during convention week, it's instructive to consider how the governor is spending his time here. His schedule reveals a sharp departure from the strategy of nominees past. The <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign has junked the nominee's ritual convention-week meetings with delegates. In the past, a fellow like <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> or <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> McGovern </PERSON> would begin his convention day with breakfast remarks to, say, the <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> delegation, and then go on to a brief appearance before, for example, the Upper Midwest Hispanic Agricultural Caucus. The <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> people have changed all that. The plans for Gov. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> this week have taken the nominee out of his party's smoke-filled buffets and instead into the community for some well-publicized, and carefully considered, public events Ranging from his Sunday night family reunion at cousin <PERSON> Pano </PERSON>'s restaurant in <LOCATION> Buckhead </LOCATION> to the Monday morning unity meeting with <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> nominee-to-be is balancing political duties with the developing imagery of a common man <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' main events were plotted in advance as symbols of three issues he hopes to pursue in his fall campaign against <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>: His concern with drug abuse, his endorsement of plant closing legislation, and his support for civil rights enforcement. An event-a-day was scheduled to demonstrate the Democratic position on these issues. For example, on Tuesday <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> traveled over to Sweet Auburn for a tour of the Martin Luther King Center. This is a man who during his 17-month primary campaign traveled to hundreds of cities in 40-odd states, who did events morning, noon and night, and it was rare that he would make his way into the black community. Right or wrong, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> simply conceded the primary black vote to <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. Against <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, he is conceding nothing, so there he was with <PERSON> Coretta </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, talking about the link between <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> immigrants and American blacks. The other major element of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' carefully crafted <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> day may be even more significant. His schedulers have allotted as much as 90 minutes a day for the governor to conduct television interviews with local TV stations around the country. This is a huge chunk of time, considering the number of party officials, fat cats and humble print journalists who would kill for a minute of the nominee's convention-week time. At the Hyatt Regency, a hotel room has been wired for video and sound; <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> merely has to walk down the hall from his suite while interviewers are shuttled in and out. Of course, the best laid plans ... many of the TV interviews have been canceled as other events crowded in, and on Monday <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had to scrap a factory gate appearance to find time for the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> parlay with <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. And at least one special interest caucus got a <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> visit _ Hispanic congressmen. All business and no pleasure would make <PERSON> Mikey </PERSON> a dull boy. And so interspersed amongst his convention events, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has found time for his daily power walk -LRB- an exercise routine, no press coverage -RRB- and for late-night family dinners.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Of course <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has n't got the only body in town. Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, the designated running mate, has a full plate of delegation breakfasts and special interest caucuses. This is how <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>'s body was being deployed on Tuesday: 8 a.m. Salute to civil rights at <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>. 10:20 a.m. Meet with <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caucus </ORGANIZATION>. 10:45 a.m. Brunch with <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> delegation. 11:45 a.m. Tour Martin Luther King Center with <PERSON> Coretta </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>. 7:30 p.m. Finance twilight supper. 9:30 p.m. Network interviews at <LOCATION> Hyatt </LOCATION>. Presumedly, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> does n't mind pulling these chores. After all, it's perfect training for the vice presidency.
