<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, a day away from his party's presidential nomination, invoked the memory of <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>. Tuesday and pledged to work to `` inspire and uplift this country The <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Democrat and his designated running mate, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, received a tour of the Martin Luther King Jr.. Center from the civil rights leader's widow, <PERSON> Coretta </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> Earlier, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, his wife, <PERSON> Kitty </PERSON>, and adviser <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> had breakfast in the candidate's hotel suite with <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> president <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirkland </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Irena </PERSON>. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' aides, sensitive to accusations that labor wields too much influence in the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, did not list the breakfast session on his schedule. An <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> spokesman called the breakfast `` routine.'' `` I'm sure what they talked about was how to win in November,'' said federation spokesman <PERSON> Rex </PERSON> <PERSON> Hardesty </PERSON>. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was spending most of the day in his suite working with speechwriter <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Woodward </PERSON> on the address he will deliver Thursday when he accepts the presidential nomination. He met for nearly an hour with the Democrats' Hispanic members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, a meeting they said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> asked for. Rep. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bustamante </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> said they talked about involving Hispanics in the campaign and in the transition team, if <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is elected. `` He wanted to establish a dialogue with the leadership of the Hispanic community in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Bustamante </PERSON>. `` We were real pleased.'' While the convention wound up its debate on the platform, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> attended a closed fund-raiser in a downtown office building. Accompanying the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor was his cousin, Academy Award-winning actress <PERSON> Olympia </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. The last threat to convention unity was resolved earlier in the day with announcement that aides to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> had reached agreement on most platform differences. With Mrs. <PERSON> King </PERSON> leading the way, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> and their wives looked at exhibits at the King Center. The first one they stopped at contained mementos of the passage of legislation establishing a national holiday commemorating King's birthday, Jan. 15 One of the exhibits was a photograph of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> signing the legislation. It included an inscription, `` To Coretta King. With respect and high esteem on a very special day.'' It was signed, `` <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>.'' The Republican vice president is <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' certain opponent in the fall election. Other exhibits included the key to Room 307 at the <PERSON> Lorraine </PERSON> <PERSON> Motel </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>. King was standing on the balcony outside that room when he was shot and killed in 1968 The Nobel Peace Prize, awarded to King, as well as the Presidential Medal of Freedom, awarded him posthumously, also were displayed. The final stop on the tour was King's tomb, inscribed, `` Rev. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> 1929 - 1968. Free at last, Free at last, Thank God almighty I'm free at last.'' In a brief speech that included several quotations from King, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> described the slain civil rights leader as `` a man of action, he was a man of inspiration.'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> was nearby, and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said that if elected he and his vice president `` are going to do our very best, with your support, to inspire and uplift this country.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> praised the convention keynote speech by <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> State Treasurer <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Richards </PERSON> and noted that neither he nor <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> `` have ever won any blue ribbons for great oratory.'' Then he added, `` And after <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> gets through tonight, none of us will meet the standard <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Richards </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> set for this convention.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was the featured convention speaker Tuesday night.
