<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Hightower scorns Bush, EMBARGOED for 9:30 pm EDT; Kennedy
remarks EMBARGOED for 9 pm; updates throughout this take</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> won the platform of his design Tuesday at the Democratic National Convention while a parade of Democrats ridiculed <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> as a `` toothache of a man,'' and worse. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> promised an emotional, late-night finale to his remarkable primary campaign. Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said it was about time for another president from <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> and scorned <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> as a `` hear-nothing, see-nothing, do-nothing vice president'' who `` was n't there, or ca n't recall, or never heard'' of the <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> arms sale. On that and other issues, <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said, `` I think it's fair to ask, where was <PERSON> George </PERSON>?'' `` <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is the man who is never there _ and he wo n't be there after the clock strikes noon on Jan. 20, 1989,'' the senator said in a prepared address that kicked off the prime-time speechmaking. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hightower </PERSON>, the tart-tongued <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> agriculture commissioner, called <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> a `` perpetual preppie,'' and said, `` He's a toothache of a man, telling us to stay the course and threatening to lead us from tweedledum to tweedledummer.'' `` He is a man who was born on third base and thinks he hit a triple,'' he said for good measure during what was billed as a presentation of platform material. The verbal abuse came after an afternoon of platform work in which <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> sought to shed the `` tax and spend'' Republican taunt. He easily defeated <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s call for higher taxes on wealthy individuals and corporations. The vote was 2,499 to 1,091. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> prevailed as well on <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s call for a `` no first use'' pledge of nuclear weapons. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s call for self-determination for Palestinians was debated and withdrawn. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> forces took the inevitable defeats with equanimity; there was little of the past emotion over Democratic ideals. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> was introduced by his 27-year-old nephew, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, son of the late president. `` For a long time I have believed that what this country needs is another president from <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>,'' said the man who tried but failed to win the party nomination in 1980. `` Now it's going to happen. President <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, it has a nice ring.''
