<HEAD>Trial Gets Under Way In Drug Agent Slaying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three Mexicans went on trial Tuesday in the abduction and killing a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> drug agent in 1985, and 124 potential jurors said they could serve for the 12 weeks the judge estimated the proceedings would take. The jurors who said they did not believe the lengthy trial would be a hardship were from a group of 200 potential panelists crowded into the courtroom of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafeedie </PERSON> amid tight security. The potential jurors were handed a questionnaire asking, among other things, about their exposure to publicity about the slaying of <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> agent <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON>. <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> was kidnapped and beaten to death shortly after he and other agents uncovered a drug trafficking operation run by <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Caro </PERSON> <PERSON> Quintero </PERSON>, who along with <PERSON> Ernesto </PERSON> <PERSON> Fonseca </PERSON> <PERSON> Carrillo </PERSON> was one of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s biggest drug kingpins, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> authorities have claimed in court documents. Facing trial in federal court here are <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> <PERSON> Alvarez </PERSON>, 28, <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Felix-Gutierrez </PERSON>, 38, and <PERSON> Rene </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Verdugo </PERSON> <PERSON> Urquidez </PERSON>, 36, who are charged in a seven-count indictment with either participating directly in the kidnap-murder of <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> or acting as an accessory. <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Marshal <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Cicchino </PERSON> imposed extra security, having officers handcuff and shackle the defendants in the courtroom whenever jurors left. Everyone entering the courthouse, including federal employees, was required to pass through metal detectors. <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> was kidnapped Feb. 7, 1985, as he left the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consulate in <LOCATION> Guadalajara </LOCATION>. Several weeks later his body and that of his pilot, <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Zavala-Avelar </PERSON>, who was kidnapped separately, were found on a remote ranch 70 miles away. <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> had been severely beaten, and documents filed on autopsy reports in connection with the case said <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON>'s jaw was broken in several places and his head was shattered `` like an eggshell.'' Also charged in the case are <PERSON> Caro </PERSON> <PERSON> Quintero </PERSON>, 33; <PERSON> Fonseca </PERSON> <PERSON> Carrillo </PERSON>, 65; <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> Espino </PERSON> <PERSON> Verdin </PERSON>, 35; <PERSON> Armando </PERSON> <PERSON> Pavon </PERSON> <PERSON> Reyes </PERSON>, 35; <PERSON> Albino </PERSON> <PERSON> Pazan </PERSON> <PERSON> Padilla </PERSON>, 27; and <PERSON> Ines </PERSON> <PERSON> Calderon </PERSON> <PERSON> Quintero </PERSON>, 33. Except for <PERSON> Calderon </PERSON> and <PERSON> Pavon </PERSON>, who remain at large, the other defendants are being held by Mexican authorities. A trial has begun in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Gurule </PERSON> said Tuesday.
