<HEAD>Tamil Rebels Kill Seven Indian Soliders In Sri Lanka</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tamil militants exploded a bomb under a patrol car in northern <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>, killing five Indian soliders, military officials said Tuesday. They said two soldiers and a rebel died in another clash. Sri Lankan military officials, who can not be identified under briefing rules, said the five died Monday when the remote-controlled bomb was detonated near the northwestern port of <LOCATION> Mannar </LOCATION>. They said two soldiers were injured and five others were reported missing in the blast. An official at the Indian High Commission, or embassy, confirmed the five deaths. The official also insisted on anonymity. A statement issued in the southern <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> city of <LOCATION> Madras </LOCATION> by the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tamil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eelam </ORGANIZATION> militia claimed 20 soldiers were killed in the blast. The <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION>, largest of the rebel groups, have exile headquarters in <LOCATION> Madras </LOCATION>. The conflicting reports could not be resolved independently. Indian troops imposed an indefinite curfew on the area to search for the missing men, the Sri Lankans said. <LOCATION> Mannar </LOCATION> is about 135 miles north of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>. On Tuesday, two Indian soldiers and a Tamil rebel were killed in an exchange of fire near the port town of <LOCATION> Batticaloa </LOCATION> in eastern <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>, the military officials said. More than 500 Indian soldiers have been killed since <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> sent an estimated 50,000 soldiers to this island nation to enforce an Indian-sponsored peace accord signed in July 1987. The accord was aimed at ending a five-year guerrilla war by the Tamils for an independent homeland in the north and east of the island. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> became involved because 60 million ethnic Tamils in southern <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> are sympathetic to the Tamil cause in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>. Tamils, mainly Hindus, make up 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million population. They claim they are discriminated against by the majority <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sinhalese </ORGANIZATION>. The Sinhalese control both the military and the government.
