<HEAD>Engineers May Have Had Clue To Space Shuttle Leak In January</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 10th graf, `He said...', to change term to tightened
sted `torqued.' Picks up 11th graf, `These two...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A pressure drop detected in January might have alerted engineers to the small leak that now threatens a long delay in the next space shuttle flight, but there is no conclusive evidence that workers acted improperly, the launch director said Tuesday. Director <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Sieck </PERSON> said a search of paperwork shows that a pressure check was made on the oxidizer tank manifold in an engine compartment before Christmas, and a second reading was taken about two weeks later. `` There was a pressure drop of about 16 pounds per square inch between the two data points,'' he said in an interview. A tiny leak of nitrogen tetroxide gas was detected in an engine compartment of space shuttle Discovery on the launch pad Friday. Engineers have been puzzling over how to fix the leak without removing the shuttle from the pad, a move that could delay the planned early September launch by two months. The leak is in a fitting on a one-half inch line leading to an oxidizer tank, the same area where the pressure drop was detected in January. `` We wish we had found it earlier,'' <PERSON> Forrest </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> McCartney </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Kennedy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, told a news conference. `` If we had found it when it was accessible, there would have been no problem. But it's in an inaccessible place, and we do n't know what we're going to do about it. `` We've got people looking at the prudent and safe thing to do,'' he said. `` What ever course we take there will be no compromise in flight safety. `` The odds are 50-50 on a rollback -LRB- of Discovery -RRB-,'' <PERSON> McCartney </PERSON> said. `` We are reviewing all procedures and documentation and equipment associated with that event,'' <PERSON> Sieck </PERSON> said of the January finding. `` We are looking at the people who performed the test.'' He said Kennedy Space Center procedures require that any leak be tightened and checked properly. `` These two data points may still have been within specifications,'' he said. `` And I would n't preclude the fact that we have other data that says the integrity of the joint was confirmed. `` Until a final review it is pure speculation that a requirement was violated and not reported,'' <PERSON> Sieck </PERSON> said. He said engineers are considering a number of options for fixing the leak. `` We're looking at a fix in place, if that's possible,'' he said. `` But we would have to assess it as safe and reliable.'' To do it properly, he said, probably would require removing the 22-foot-tall engine compartment, a difficult task never before done on the pad. Another option would be to take Discovery to a hangar and as soon as possible replace the compartment with one being prepared for a shuttle Atlantis flight in November. Such a move would eliminate the need to wait for a leak repair and could cut the launch delay time to about a month. `` And I would n't preclude a quick fix with some old-fashioned Yankee ingenuity,'' he said. Flying with the leak as is a possibility, `` but we would have to assure ourselves that it would be absolutely safe,'' <PERSON> Sieck </PERSON> said. Nitrogen tetroxide combines with a fuel to power the steering engines in flight. If the leak continued in orbit, it ideally would vaporize and drift off into space. However, the possibility of it hitting a cold surface might cause it to vaporize and pool in the engine pod, where fire could occur if it somehow contacted the fue. Meanwhile, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> moved ahead with a plan to test-fire Discovery's three main engines on the launch pad on July 28 The main engines are separate from the steering engine system containing the leak. Discovery is being grooomed to make the first shuttle mission since Challenger exploded Jan. 28, 1986, killing the seven crew members. Five veteran shuttle astronauts are to make the four-day flight during which they will release a communications satellite and conduct experiments.
</TEXT>
