<HEAD>England's Beacon Party Remembers The Armada</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-8 UPDATE with beacons lighted, details. Picks up
9th graf pvs, Queen Elizabeth ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A chain of beacons burst into flame across <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> on Tuesday night in memory of the fiery warning to the nation when the Spanish Armada was sighted exactly 400 years ago. Spanish Ambassador <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Bellacasa </PERSON>, letting bygones be bygones, used a long-handled, flaming torch to fire the first beacon on a damp and drizzly night. `` Two old countries like ours have to build, on our history, better understanding and friendship in the future,'' he told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. The event was shown live on national TV as the ambassador lit the fuel in a big iron brazier atop an oak pole at the Kynance headland. The area near Lizard village in the southwest tip of <LOCATION> Cornwall </LOCATION> is where local people say the Armada was first sighted. The lighting was followed swiftly by the chain of beacons and wigwam-shaped bonfires that extended to the Scottish border, 430 miles away. `` I invited the ambassador to light the first beacon because I thought it was about time, after 400 years, that we buried this old hatchet in a symbolic way,'' said <PERSON> Bruno </PERSON> <PERSON> Peek </PERSON>, who organized the event and called it `` Fire Over <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>.'' The Spanish Armada's 125 ships carried 19,000 soldiers, 8,000 sailors, 2,000 galley slaves and 180 monks and friars, sent by <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> king of <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, to overthrow <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>'s Protestant Queen <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Legend </PERSON> has it that <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON>'s favorite captain, Sir <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Drake </PERSON>, was involved in a lawn-bowling game in <LOCATION> Plymouth </LOCATION> as the great fleet approached and was so unflustered that he insisted on finishing the game before going to his ship Queen <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> is to visit <LOCATION> Plymouth </LOCATION> on Thursday to join Armada festivities in the city from which <PERSON> Drake </PERSON> sailed into action. Everyone seemed to be in on the fun _ even the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, which issued 40 million stamps depicting galleons and cannon smoke. A breakfast cereal company offered `` Armada Treasure Replica Coins.'' The replicas are copied from coins found in Armada ships wrecked by gales as the great fleet struggled home after failing to link up with a <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> invasion army waiting in the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>. Historians have argued long over whether the English or the gales defeated the Armada. `` The weather did help but the defeat was a great victory for <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> because it raised the hearts of men in dark hours,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Mildren </PERSON>, a historian specializing in Armada lore. <PERSON> Tamsin </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, responsible for 10 of <LOCATION> Cornwall </LOCATION>'s 20 fires, said the villagers in Lizard had been celebrating all day, as they have done every anniversary for four centuries. She said the Kynance beacon, mounted on a 30-foot oak pole, had a trial firing Tuesday morning and burned for an hour with a bright orange flame. `` We are also having 2,000 pounds -LRB- $ 3,360 dollars -RRB- worth of fireworks and I was astonished to find when we opened the boxes that they were made in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Kitchen </PERSON>, a schoolmaster who has studied the matter, said the early-warning system of beacons and fires was unique to <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and could muster up to 30,000 men within two hours. He said the procedure lasted to the 19th century, when there was a threat of invasion by <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON>'s armies, and there is a record of one sentinel setting his beacon alight and frying sausages. `` In setting up the new beacons, we worked from secret Elizabethan diagrams which showed pitch at the center, covered by anything dry and combustible, topped by a thatch to keep out rain and the whole thing covered with brushwood,'' said <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION>, which looks after historic sites and buildings. `` The trick was to build a fire that would quickly produce a flame at night and a lot of smoke in the daytime.''
