<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Riot police wounded five people and arrested at least 270 protesters Tuesday when a nationwide general strike flared into street clashes and induced leftist guerrilla violence, officials and strike leaders said. Three of the wounded were strikers and two were children, reports said. Also on Tuesday, rebels of the Maoist-oriented Shining Path organization killed six police defenders and wounded five in an attack against a police post in <LOCATION> Pozuzo </LOCATION>, a jungle town 170 miles east of <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>, police said. The night before, officers reported, guerrillas shot dead a policeman in the nearby town of <LOCATION> Tochache </LOCATION>. The 48-hour general strike began on Tuesday to protest government economic policy. Strikers and student sympathizers blocked main arteries leading into <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> with bonfires and rocks but were driven off by police using tear gas and firing water cannons, reporters said. Police quickly reopened the roads. Officers said a train carrying workers to their jobs in <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Chosica </LOCATION>, 25 miles away, was halted midway when saboteurs blew up a small section of track. The train stopped in time and no one was hurt. The communist-led General Confederation of Peruvian Workers said 80 percent of factories, stores and businesses in this capital city were closed Tuesday. <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> del </PERSON> <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON> called the strike a failure and said business activity was almost normal. Most banks and government offices in downtown <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> opened late with about half their workers, the government said, and school attendence was low. It blamed the absenteeism on an estimated 50 percent cut in bus transportation. About half the shops and stores in downtown <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> remained shuttered. The confederation claims 90 percent of this Andean nation's 1.6 million unionized workers as members. It called the strike to protest government austerity measures imposed this month that include food price increases ranging from 20 percent to 100 percent. It is the third general strike against the 3-year-old government of President <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>, a Social Democrat. The development comes with the economy in a tailspin, a steep fiscal deficit and an inflation rate estimated to hit 400 percent in 1988. The government declared the strike illegal and dispatched 8,000 police and army troops to patrol <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> and ride public buses to ensure security. Police said 220 protesters were arrested in sporadic clashes in <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Huancayo </LOCATION>, 125 miles east of <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>, 50 demonstrators were arrested in a march and a 10-year-old boy was injured by a tear gas cannister, police said. Strike leader <PERSON> Alberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON> said police shot and wounded three protesters and a child during a march in <LOCATION> Juliaca </LOCATION>, 600 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>. His charges could not be confirmed with police. Radio Programas, <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s leading news station, said business activity was greatly reduced in the key highland capitals of <LOCATION> Huancayo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cuzco </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Puno </PERSON>, while interstate trucking was virtually halted nationwide. An indefinite strike by miners entered its second day Tuesday, paralyzing most mining across the nation, strike officials said. Police said leftist guerrillas supporting the strike since Monday exploded a car bomb in <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>, wounding three people, and launched bomb attacks against buildings in other cities, but no reports emerged of other injuries. Shining Path guerrillas blew up power pylons and blacked out <LOCATION> Ayacucho </LOCATION>, 225 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>.
