<HEAD>Wyoming Fire Close to Yellowstone; Alaska Fires Allowed to Burn</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Calif. crew forced to take
refuge from fire, delete outdated reference to all fires in Oregon
being contained, picking up 4th graf pvs `The northern...'. SUBS
final graf to add detail on new Oregon fire.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos SC4, GJ1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE BUCKLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Crews used natural barriers to keep a 14,000-acre wildfire in <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>'s Teton Wilderness from reaching summer homes Tuesday, while officials in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> left fires that have charred more than a half-million acres to die on their own. Firefighters in northwestern <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> got a little break in the weather, which helped contain all but two of 15 fires that consumed more than 20,000 acres of range and pinon juniper. Fires also burned Tuesday in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, but none threatened populated areas and most were small. A blaze swept over a firefighting crew near <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, about 45 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>, but the workers surivived by taking refuge in portable fireproof shelters, said <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Terrill </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forestry </ORGANIZATION>. The northern edge of the lightning-sparked fire in <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> was closing in on Yellowstone National Park, but was allowed to burn since it's on <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> land and not a threat. However, 550 firefighters used natural firebreaks like streams and rock formations to keep the southern border of the fire from reaching a small colony of summer homes in <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, 12 miles away. Officials said unless heavy rains fall soon, it's likely the fire will burn until snow puts it out no later than September. In <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, five major fires accounted for almost 450,000 acres of the total. Nearly a third went up in a blaze near <LOCATION> Livengood </LOCATION>, about 60 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Fairbanks </LOCATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Sue </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>. Rugged territory in the <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> fire, at an elevation of about 8,500 feet and in prime grizzly bear habitat, has complicated firefighting. `` We're not only shuttling crews -LRB- by helicopter -RRB- to the fireline, but during the day we're moving the crews around,'' Fire Information Officer <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Huntington </PERSON> said Tuesday. `` Normally they would be able to walk from point to point, but because of the rugged terrain and downed timber ... we're moving the crews around. If we do n't do that, they're worn out by the time they arrive on the spot where they're supposed to be fighting the fire.'' The crews have little more than picks, shovels and the water tanks they carry on their backs to fight the flames. In <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION>, to the north of the Teton Wilderness, officials monitored several fires covering 11,000 acres. While all <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION>'s roads and front-country campsites were open, campfire restrictions were imposed throughout the park's back-country, where fire danger forced the closing of some campsites <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> officials generally let the fires burn unless they threaten lives or property, critical wildlife habitat or commercial timber, said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Frey </PERSON>, fire coordinator for the <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. The fires open up dense stands of unproductive black spruce, said <PERSON> Frey </PERSON>. Natural revegetation of burned areas with willow, grass and berries provides food for many of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s big game species. Animals usually move away from the flames well before they are endangered, and few die in the fires. <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> officials also tend to let fires burn themselves out. `` We've had several questions on that, and the majority are probably coming from some local guides and outfitters,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> fire information officer <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Huntington </PERSON>. `` They're for a good reason concerned that this fire would destroy some prime habitat where they take hunters in for big game hunts, and packers in for some hikes.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> held a public meeting in <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION> to let the outfitters and guides discuss their concerns and so the agency can explain its fire management decisions, <PERSON> Huntington </PERSON> said. The low humidity and dry brush fueled the <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> fires, which caused no structural damage despite threatening the town of Dinosaur and the headquarters of <ORGANIZATION> Dinosaur </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monument </ORGANIZATION> on Sunday. Only one injury was reported, on Tuesday, when a firefighter at the Flatiron fire near Rifle got cinders in his eyes. Fire information officer <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Dove </PERSON> said the man was treated at a local hospital and released. The <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> fires were being fueled by dry brush, high temperatures and low humidity, officials said. In <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, fires that apparently had been set were contained Monday and early Tuesday, but not before destroying a home and two other buildings in <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION>. And in southern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, an all-out air and ground assault by 1,000 firefighters went a long way toward extinguishing