<HEAD>Activists Say Aid Convoy to Nicaragua Helped By U.S. Delay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Veterans' Peace Convoy of 31 American activists taking humanitarian aid to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> was helped by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government's attempt to keep it from crossing the border, members said Tuesday. `` The publicity helped us greatly, and poor people came to us throughout our trip to <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, pushing coins into our hands and saying, ` This is the least we can do,''' said convoy coordinator <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Valdez </PERSON>, 40, of <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. `` The support of Mexicans has been great.'' The caravan crossed the Mexican border at <LOCATION> Nuevo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Laredo </LOCATION> on July 14. It now has 20 trucks with 20 tons of supplies. The activists, who oppose <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy aimed at overthrowing <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s leftist Sandinista government, spoke with reporters after rain washed out a planned demonstration in front of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>. They originally planned to reach <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> in June to donate food, medicine and other supplies, but were delayed by <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> refusal to let them cross the border at <LOCATION> Laredo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government said that leaving the trucks in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, as they plan to do, would violate a 3-year-old trade embargo. Now the schedule calls for arriving in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> on July 27 after traveling through <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. Members of the group praised the hospitality they received in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. `` It's been fantastic,'' said <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Breindel </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` We stopped to ask this guy for directions to a hotel in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, and he just offered this compound where we could park our trucks and a place to stay for the night.'' The American visitors noted that the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> arranged an official escort for their stay in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. If they return to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> without the trucks, the activists face up to a $ 50,000 fine and 10 years in jail each. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government said the vehicles could be used by <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s Sandinista government for military purposes and thus were subject to the trade embargo Before the group entered <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Customs agents `` asked us to sign a form that said we would promise to bring the trucks back,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Silk </PERSON>, 60, a World War II Merchant Marine veteran from <LOCATION> Stonington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION> `` It was another attempt to make it impossible for us to continue our journey,'' said <PERSON> Silk </PERSON>, adding that no one signed the document. Silk's truck is carrying more than 1,000 pounds of paper donated by a local <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> organization to print a Bible in the language of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s Sumo Indians. Other activists are bringing food, medicines and medical equipment. The convoy also has sent 300,000 tons of goods by ship to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, whose government celebrated the ninth anniversary Tuesday of its revolutionary victory over the rightist <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON> dynasty that ruled <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> for four decades. Convoy leaders said they hope to obtain a ruling in federal court exempting their trucks from the Nicaraguan embargo. But they said that even if it's not forthcoming they wo n't change their plans. `` We're going to donate this assistance to humanitarian organizations for the relief of human suffering,'' said <PERSON> Valdez </PERSON>, a veteran of the Vietnam War. `` For that we'll risk any charges.''
