<HEAD>Iran Says U.N. Chief Could Declare Immediate Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-6 UPDATE with Iraqi sources doubting cease-fire
will come soon. Picks up 4th graf pvs, Mahallati said ... editing
15th graf pvs, Foreign Minister ... to conform</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> condemned Tuesday's Iraqi raids against Iranian targets, accused the <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> government of sabotaging peace efforts and said the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> chief could declare the start of a truce `` at this very moment.'' But senior <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> sources at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, speaking on condition of anonymity, said they doubted that Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> would succeed in his aim of achieving a cease-fire in a week to 10 days. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s foreign minister said in <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> on Tuesday that until <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> takes concrete action toward achieving peace, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> must keep on with the war. On Monday, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> declared after a year's delay that it unconditionally accepts <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> Resolution 598 which demands an immediate truce and troop withdrawal and sets out a peace plan to end the 8-year-old Iran-Iraq war. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> ambassador, <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Ja'afar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahallati </PERSON>, spelled out <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s views after meeting <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> and after lodging a formal protest with the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> over <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s air raids on a nuclear facility and other targets. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> said the air strikes were prompted by Iranian attacks. <PERSON> Mahallati </PERSON> said he told the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> chief `` that in the view of the authorities of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, the secretary-general ... has a totally free hand to declare D-Day at this very moment, which means starting implementation of Resolution 598.'' D-Day is the day on which a cease-fire would begin. It would be set by the secretary-general after consultations with both sides. <PERSON> Mahallati </PERSON> called the air strikes `` a deliberate attempt to sabotage the work of the secretary-general and the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> ... to put an immediate end to this aggressive war initiated by <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> held urgent consultations with <PERSON> Mahallati </PERSON> and later with Iraqi Ambassador <PERSON> Ismat </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kittani </PERSON> to discuss putting the resolution into effect and the latest <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> attacks. The <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> held closed-door consultations on Resolution 598 and on <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s demand to condemn the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> destruction of an Iranian airliner July 3. The consultations ended Tuesday night without any decision or statement and are scheduled to resume Wednesday. The secretary-general's spokesman, <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON>, told reporters the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> chief believes `` the continuation of hostilities is a clear sign that the cease-fire must come into place as soon as possible.'' <PERSON> Mahallati </PERSON> urged the council in a letter to condemn the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> attack which, he said, `` so defiantly mocks all efforts for attainment of a peaceful end to the conflict.'' Some diplomats said procedural matters, including translating <PERSON> Mahallati </PERSON>'s letter into other official <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> languages, would have to precede council discussion of this latest complaint. The diplomats spoke on condition of anonymity. The protest was lodged hours before the council was to discuss the shooting down of an Iranian airliner by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> missile cruiser <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION>, which mistook it for an attacking warplane. All 290 people on board were killed. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has not obtained council condemnation of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> action and negotiations were under way to reach a compromise statement which would be acceptable to all parties. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Aziz </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> was `` on guard'' against Iranian intentions and believed its decision to accept the cease-fire plan known as Resolution 598 `` might be a tactical decision aimed at winning time or decoying, with the aim of surprising us by initiating hostilities or preparing for more aggression.'' <PERSON> Aziz </PERSON> said that until <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> takes tangible steps toward peace and demonstrates its sincerity, `` it is logical to act as if the war is still going on.'' On Tuesday <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> hit Iranian targets and Iranian warplanes retaliated by raiding a dam in <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> said a year ago that it accepts the resolution to end the war that began in September 1980 if <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> does. <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> at the time withheld endorsement, saying <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> had to be branded the aggressor before there could be peace. Among other provisions, Resolution 598 calls for a prisoner exchange, an impartial body to determine which side was the aggressor and massive international reconstruction aid.
