<HEAD>Amnesty International Details Egyptian Torture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> called on <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> Wednesday to protect political detainees who claim they were beaten with cables and whips, given electric shocks and burned with cigarettes while in detention. The international human rights organization said evidence it compiled since 1981 indicated a continuing pattern of torture by security and other officials working in Egyptian prisons and detention centers. In June, 44 security, prison and police officials accused of torturing political prisoners from 1981-83 were acquitted after a trial in <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>. Former detainees identified some of them as their torturers, <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement. The group said in a 50-page report that its evidence of the beatings, shocks and burns comes from interviews with victims and from medical reports by the Egyptian <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'s forensic medicine department. Doctors examining detainees who said they were tortured found in many cases physical scarring consistent with the complaints. Many reports of torture followed the arrest of thousands of political suspects after the attempted assassinations in May and August last year of two former interior ministers, Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Basha </PERSON> and Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Nabawi </PERSON> <PERSON> Ismail </PERSON>, and magazine editor <PERSON> Makram </PERSON> <PERSON> Muhammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON>, the group said. Most of those arrested were supporters of Islamic groups, and said they were blindfolded and could not identify their torturers, it said. An Amnesty official attended part of the 18-month-long <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION> trial. The organization said it is still assessing the trial outcome, but that it did not want the acquittals to signify an end to efforts by <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> to end torture of political prisoners. The report was written after two missions to <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> and extensive talks with government officials there, the group said. The report recommended structural reforms within the country, noting that <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>'s state of emergency has facilitated prolonged detention. The state of emergency began after the 1981 assassination of President <PERSON> Anwar </PERSON> <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON> by Islamic fundamentalists. <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> was among the first six countries to become party to a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> convention against torture.
