<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday that high Israeli officials have `` tolerated if not encouraged'' the use of firearms against Palestinian demonstrators and expressed concern that `` so few'' cases are investigated. The London-based human rights group said bullets fired by <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldiers killed at least 160 Palestinians, including women and 55 people under age 18, in the occupied territories. According to <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> figures Tuesday, 225 Palestinians and four Israelis died in the <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> uprising in the occupied territories since it began Dec. 8. Amnesty said in a statement released by its <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> office that it asked <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> for a clarification on its policy and information on investigations in the killing of Palestinians by the Israeli army. `` On the basis of available evidence, <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> authorities at high levels tolerated if not encouraged the ill considered and excessive use of firearms,'' <PERSON> Amnesty </PERSON> said in the statement. It also said it was very concerned that `` few cases have been the object of investigation.'' Amnesty asked <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to explain the directives in force on the use of firearms and to provide the number of cases in which a serious and thorough investigation was opened into the killing of a Palestinian. The group also asked <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to explain how it reached its conclusions in investigations already completed, and to say if or when members of the <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> army were tried or disciplined for killing a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> demonstrator.
