<FIRST>a a AM-ReligionToday Adv22   07-19 0839</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Religion Today, Adv 22,0866</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, July 22, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Leaders Seek To Safeguard Religious Liberty Guarantees</HEAD>
<NOTE>With Laserphoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A broad cross-section of American leaders says a distinctive hallmark of the nation _ free, non-established religion _ is threatened by modern battling over it. They've sought to stake out some common ground to protect that principle of religious liberty. In the conflicts, the pendulum was described as having swung in American history from one pole to another _ from religious to secular semi-establishments. But the standard is set by Constitution's First Amendment: `` <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> shall make no law regarding an establishment of religion, or prohibiting the free exercise thereoff.'' In the shifting applications of these doubled-edged clauses, controversy lately has ballooned and confusion multiplied about relationships of church and state, faith and politics. The issue has frayed political campaigns and engulfed the courts. More lawsuits about it have landed in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in the last 25 years than in all the nation's previous history. The `` controversies over religion in public life pose both a danger and an opportunity,'' says an unusual, new document, the <LOCATION> Williamsburg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Charter </LOCATION>, backed by a wide spectrum of religious, academic, business and political leaders. Citing dangers either of forcing religion out of public affairs or, in reaction, politicizing faith for laws to establish a `` <LOCATION> Christian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' the charter calls for a `` renewed national compact'' about it. Social scientist Os Guinness of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, head of the project, says `` any sense of shared agreement about the place of religion and politics has broken down.'' He says `` recurring conflicts and the flood of cases about textbooks, prayer, abortion, and an infinite number of things'' will intensify unless there is a process for restored consensus. `` It's important not just to religion but to democracy,'' he said in an interview. `` Without it, there's danger down the line.'' He described the new charter, already endorsed by about 150 national leaders in various fields and expected to be signed by many others in state meetings this fall, as like the `` Queensbury Rules'' that restrained boxing from sheer destructiveness. `` It sets forth the place of religion in public life _ that's the heart of it _ and also guiding principles by which people of different religions or none can debate and contend robustly but with civility,'' he said The 6,000-word charter says the constitution's `` religious liberty provisions hold the key to <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> distinctiveness and American destiny.'' The guaranteed rights depend on recognition that `` they are neither given by the state, nor can they be taken away by the state,'' but are inherent in belief in the `` inviolability of the human person,'' the charter says. It says the meaning of those provisions is ignored whenever `` the logic of arguments favors either an unwarranted intrusion of religion into public life or an unwarranted exclusion of religion from it.'' Until well into the 20th century, the charter says that there was a `` de facto semi-establishment'' of a generalized Protestantism, especially in the public schools. But now, the tendency was seen as swinging the other way `` toward the de facto semi-establishment of a wholly secular understanding'' of humanity and public institutions. The charter aims at mapping a middle course between the secular left, which has worked to push religion out of public life, and the religious right, which wants religious premises to predominate. The document, drawn up by the <ORGANIZATION> Williamsburg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Charter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, a private, public-policy organization funded by individuals and corporations, has gained an impressive array of backers. They include present and former chief justices, the chairmen of the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committees </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> members, corporate executives, educators and various faith leaders, evangelical and mainline. However, it so far has n't gained support of some aggressive antagonists such as the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, which opposes religion in the public sphere, and Moral Majority, which wants them prevailing there. The charter says religion too often is dimissed as a `` purely private matter,'' but this ignores the fact that the American system depends on `` ultimate beliefs, for otherwise we have no right to the rights'' it upholds. The First Amendment guarantee of no interference with religion puts `` religious expression on an equal footing with all other forms of expressing in genuinely public forums,'' the charter says. It says that some in recent disputes have `` insisted that any evidence of religious influence on public policy represents an establishment of religion and is therefore precluded ... `` Such exclusion of religion from public life is historically unwarranted, philosophically inconsistent and profoundly undemocratic ... Many of the most dynamic social movements in American history, including that of civil rights, were legitimately inspired and shaped by religious motivation.'' However, the document criticizes religionists who `` bring to politics a misplaced absoluteness that idolizes politics, ` Satanizes' their enemies and politicizes their own faith.'' In the conflict, participants often have been acrimonious and unfair, the charter says, urging greater balance, mutual respect and civility.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, July 22</NOTE>
