<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Causing damage to religious property or interfering with a person's free exercise of religion is now a federal crime under a law recently approved by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and signed by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. It makes those who engage in interstate activity to damage religious property because of its religious character or obstruct by force or threat anyone's free exercise of religion subject to fines and prison sentences. In debate on the legislation, members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> pointed to increased incidents of religious violence and vandalism. Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, D-Ill., said, `` <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is sending a clear signal that the desecrations, the injuries, the deaths are intolerable in a free society such as ours.
