<HEAD>NORFOLK: at all.'</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 In a step toward consumer protection, he promised the federal government would survey success rates of all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> in vitro clinics and make the results public. Dr. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Marrs </PERSON>, director of the in vitro center at <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>' Hospital of the Good Samaritan, testified that even though regulation of reproductive medicine is a sensitive issue, `` the procedures performed are potentially dangerous without standard licensing of the facilities and personnel.'' Government involvement is not something that medicine normally seeks. But <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, too, chastised <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for staying away from infertility research. `` The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> have never provided any funds for in vitro fertilization or its offshoots -LRB- such as transfer of egg and sperm directly to the Fallopian tubes, and embryo freezing for later implant -RRB- because of pressures which the politicians are not willing to buck,'' he said. Federal regulations require that a special Ethics Advisory Board approve government-funded in vitro research, but since 1980 no Secretary of <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> has appointed the board. A de facto moratorium has resulted, and Mrs. <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Miranda </PERSON>, who says federal funding would ensure better-controlled research, blames it on `` right-to-lifers'' within and without the government. For some, ethical difficulties arise as soon as embryos are created, the central part of the in vitro process and of research to improve the technique. `` I think it's just a straight-out fear of touching upon the whole issue of abortion,'' asserted <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Caplan </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION>'s Center for Biomedical Ethics. The <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>, in its 1987 `` Instruction on Respect for Human Life,'' recognized `` no moral distinction'' between embryos at the moment of conception and fetuses and fully developed humans; they must be protected equally. Yet many physicians and ethicists do make distinctions and consider medical research using embryos to be justifiable. Regardless of the controversy, <PERSON> Caplan </PERSON> argues, the government has an obligation not to evade an issue that affects so many Americans. `` It just shows a culpable lack of leadership.'' At a congressional hearing earlier this month, Rep. <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, sought to find out why the <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has declined to appoint the required ethics board. For years, the agency fended off the question. A 1986 memo by an <ORGANIZATION> HHS </ORGANIZATION> staff member to Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Windom </PERSON>, assistant secretary for health, suggested <PERSON> Windom </PERSON> could reply to the American Association for the <ORGANIZATION> Advancement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION>'s call for an ethics board by sending a letter that was `` warm, but noncommittal.'' The memo said the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> saw `` advantages in proceeding as we have, avoiding cost and controversy associated with a permanent board.'' Finally, facing the <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> panel this July 14, the department was ready to respond more fully. Just two days earlier, <PERSON> Windom </PERSON> testified, <ORGANIZATION> HHS </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Otis </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON> had agreed to re-establish the board. First, however, the board's `` charter'' must be re-defined and the new scope and purpose published in the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Register </ORGANIZATION>, followed by a 60-day public comment period. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration could be out of office by then. `` They've timed it obviously so they can be free of controversy,'' <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. Nor are the issues of right and wrong simple in this uncharted realm. In the <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>'s labs, among others, researchers are trying to find a way to help in those cases in which a husband does not produce the millions of sperm needed for natural fertilization. With micro-injection, directly into the egg, only one sperm would be needed. A purely humanitarian avenue of research to which no one could object? Ethicists wonder. Which one sperm? Will it produce a boy or a girl? Who chooses? Who's responsible if the baby is abnormal? For another question, the response is clearer: Why have couples continued to pursue in vitro for a decade, despite its uncertainties? The answer is in a portrait on the wall in <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>' office, showing twinkly-eyed twin girls who'll be 3 next month: <PERSON> Heather </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>. The day the <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> opened, <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> was at the door, the first to sign up for in vitro. `` I'd had several operations to correct problems,'' she explained. `` You just have a drive to have a child.'' Seven failures later, however, she'd given up. She and her husband, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON>, had been `` saving every penny'' for years for the procedures; she was 38 and emotionally spent. `` When it did n't work,'' she said, `` it was just like a death had occurred.'' Still, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> asked her to make one last try. A month after the implant, the phone call from the clinic finally came. It was Christmastime _ and Mrs. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>'s present was two tiny heartbeats. She caught her breath, then shouted, then wept. At last, it was time for the announcement she'd ached to make. `` I asked my mother, ` Do you still believe in miracles?' She just looked at me,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> recalled. `` I said, ` I'm going to have a baby.'''
