<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At The Movies: ``Short Circuit 2,'' ``A Summer Story''</HEAD>
<TEXT>

</TEXT>
<HEAD>``Short Circuit 2''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 In a summer that delivered an army of dwarfs and an extremely charming rabbit to movie theaters, one might wonder whether a talking robot is a little much. No way! `` Short Circuit 2,'' a sequel to the original of a few seasons back, is a sweet surprise package that will charm your socks off. Its star is unquestionably a robot, but never has a hunk of metal been quite so adorable. If you remember the first, `` Short Circuit,'' the creature dubbed `` Number Five'' was invented as a tool of war. But the robot was struck by lightning, reprogrammed itself and escaped from the military. `` Number Five is alive!'' said promos for the first movie. Now, two years later, the robot has taken a human name _ <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Five </PERSON> _ and his adventurous spirit craves `` input,'' information on the world around him. Meanwhile, his inventor, <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Jahrvi </PERSON>, an Indian who speaks <PERSON> Malaprop </PERSON>, has fallen on hard times. Fired from the military, the inventor, played by <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, has taken to selling miniature <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Fives </PERSON> on streetcorners. A department store buyer falls in love with the toys, orders 1,000 of them and the plot is off and running. When <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Five </PERSON> is shipped to the big city to help with toy production, the country-bred robot's circuits get overloaded with `` input.'' Adventures abound. <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Five </PERSON> gets involved with street hoodlums and bank robbers and becomes the intermediary in a love affair. He gets mugged, hugged and spray painted with graffiti. And he tries on an array of colorful outfits seeking his own fashion image. When he's pushed out the window of a 34-story skyscraper, <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Five </PERSON> has a magical way out. After all, this is a fairy tale. The gleaming backdrop, by the way, is <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>. In various action scenes, <PERSON> Johny </PERSON> <PERSON> Five </PERSON> flies, swings from a crane, and dizzily spins two villains who intrude upon the toy factory. Johnny Five is supported by some able human actors. In addition to <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> as the addled <PERSON> Jahrvi </PERSON>, there's <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> McKean </PERSON> as a small-time hustler whose baser instincts are reformed by <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Five </PERSON>'s friendship. The always amusing <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Weston </PERSON> is a sneaky villain named <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON>. <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>'s direction of the script by <PERSON> S.S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Brent </PERSON> <PERSON> Maddock </PERSON> keeps things moving at a breathtaking pace and focuses always on the man of the hour _ our iron-clad Superman. `` Short Circuit 2'' is rated PG, presumably for some fairly mild language and violence -LRB- to a robot? -RRB-. Take the kids by all means. _ ^ By <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Deutsch </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>

</TEXT>
<HEAD>``A Summer Story''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` A Summer Story'' is a sad, beautiful romance of human choices and regrets, and of how love sometimes fails to overcome differences between people. Set in the gorgeous <LOCATION> Devon </LOCATION> countryside just after the turn of the century, the film focuses on upper-class Londoner <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashton </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilby </PERSON> -RRB-, who is spending a holiday trekking through the moors when he twists his ankle. While recovering, he rents a room in a farmhouse, where he soon falls in love with the incredibly pretty <PERSON> Megan </PERSON>, a farm girl portrayed by film newcomer <PERSON> Imogen </PERSON> <PERSON> Stubbs </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shakespeare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Ashton </PERSON>'s presence is resented by farm owner Mrs. <PERSON> Narracombe </PERSON> -LRB- <LOCATION> Susannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> -RRB- and by her son, <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Jerome </PERSON> <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON> -RRB-, who long has hoped to marry <PERSON> Megan </PERSON>. After a few idyllic and clandestine midnight meetings, the young lovers must part, although <PERSON> Ashton </PERSON> promises to return to fetch <PERSON> Megan </PERSON>. The outcome of this romance is influenced by the social class boundaries so rigid in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> before World War I. But the choices <PERSON> Ashton </PERSON> faces also deal with timeless issues of commitment, responsibility and free will. Directed by <PERSON> Piers </PERSON> <PERSON> Haggard </PERSON>, `` A Summer Story'' is being shown in theaters only in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and perhaps up to 50 other big cities. It is a quiet film unlikely to attract the mass audience drawn by blockbusters and adventure movies. But it belongs to a too often overlooked class of films that deal with real people and genuine human emotions _ films that touch the heart and the brain rather than blast the eardrums. <PERSON> Penelope </PERSON> <PERSON> Mortimer </PERSON>'s screenplay is based on `` The Apple Tree,'' a classic romance story written in 1916 by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Galsworthy </PERSON>, the British author best known for his `` Forsyte Saga'' trilogy. `` A Summer Story,'' released by <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, was produced by <PERSON> Danton </PERSON> <PERSON> Rissner </PERSON>. It is rated PG-13, with adult themes and some sex and nudity. Running time: 95 minutes. _ ^ By <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Motion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Picture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> rating definitions: G _ General audiences. All ages admitted. PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be suitable for children. PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young children. R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult guardian. X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age restrictions.
