<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN WINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>

</TEXT>
<HEAD>``Scenes From the Southside'' (RCA) _ Bruce Hornsby and the</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Range While `` Scenes From the Southside'' is n't the first music to evoke the atmosphere of <LOCATION> Appalachia </LOCATION>, it may be the first to do it with a piano rather than a mandolin, banjo or fiddle. But few records have a stronger sense of a region than the second album from <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Hornsby </PERSON> and the Range. <PERSON> Hornsby </PERSON> pleads for preservation of the environment on `` Look Out Any Window,'' sings about a small-town scandal on `` The <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Road </LOCATION>'' and jabs fundamentalist preachers common to the region on `` <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON>'s Ladder'' and `` Defenders of the Flag.'' <PERSON> Hornsby </PERSON> and his brother and writing partner, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hornsby </PERSON>, show a novelist's eye for detail in describing the area where they were raised. <PERSON> Hornsby </PERSON>'s piano is more dominant than on the band's first album, the hit `` The Way It Is.'' <PERSON> Hornsby </PERSON>, who gives himself plenty of time for solos on the 48-minute record, has a jazzy sense of phrasing that recalls <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Jarrett </PERSON>, but he plays with a <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> Lewis-like velocity. It's a unique blend, and one to be embraced by listeners weary of synthesizers. The record could use more diversity in tempo and instrumentation; for example, <PERSON> Hornsby </PERSON> makes little use of his skill on the accordian. Such quibbles aside, `` Scenes From the Southside'' is an album delivered with considerable honesty and heart.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>

</TEXT>
<HEAD>``Diesel and Dust'' (Columbia) _ Midnight Oil</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 If <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> would adopt `` Dream World'' from Midnight Oil's new album as his campaign theme, he'd beat the Republicans in a landslide The song is a sure vote-getter that sounds celebratory for Democrats, ominous for the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION>. `` Your dream world is just about to end,'' Midnight Oil lead singer <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> snarls above chiming guitars that provide the wake-up call. The song, written with the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> revolution in mind, is killer rock' n' roll _ hook-filled, dance-inducing and thought-provoking all at once. Happily, the rest of `` Diesel and Dust'' is of the same caliber as `` Dream World,'' and the album could allow Midnight Oil a break into the American market. Until now, the veteran Australian quintet's socially conscious music has n't found much of an audience in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. But Midnight Oil deserves to be heard. Its sound reflects five-star bands from other eras, including the Clash and the <ORGANIZATION> Byrds </ORGANIZATION>. While <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> sounds like a world-weary <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Strummer </PERSON>, bassist <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Gifford </PERSON> and guitarists <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Moginie </PERSON> and <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Rotsey </PERSON> play with both finesse and fire to help create music that is catchy and yet thundering. The band must be great live. And its message is strong. Besides the call to activism on `` Dream World,'' <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> sings about the arms race on `` Put Down That Weapon'' and addresses land rights on `` Beds Are Burning.'' Social concerns have become a more prominent part of pop music in recent years, so there should be room on the charts for Midnight Oil.
</TEXT>
