<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Brother-Sister Duo Is Newest Family Act</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Sanders have swapped rowdy Alaskan bars for more gentle settings to sing their songs of love. After fighting off grizzly bears and gold thieves in the land of the midnight sun, the brother-sister duo came to <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> with their close-knit vocals and launched a country music recording career. <PERSON> Vicki </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON>, 31, and <PERSON> Dale </PERSON>, 33, spent the past 10 years singing in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> at night and often mining for gold by day with their father, a retired geology teacher. `` It was very rewarding,'' <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON> said. `` It was nice being able to make people smile all the time.'' <PERSON> Vicki </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON> gave a sample of their experiences: _ `` We played in <LOCATION> Barrow </LOCATION> in the far northern part. We were hired with 13 Colombians who never went to sleep; they partied nonstop. There were two buckets for the bathroom and a shower stall that said ` girls Monday-Wednesday-Friday' and ` boys Tuesday-Thursday.''' _ `` In <PERSON> Seward </PERSON>, a girl was beating a guy up. She picked up a chair and threw it at him. He ran into the bathroom and hid. He stepped out and she sucker - punched him. _ `` A guy threatened to tie his wife to a tree, so she shot him nine times with a .22 at their cabin. She got on a snow machine and went for help.'' The darkness and remoteness of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> seemed to affect the residents, the <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON> said. `` In all those remote places where it's dark, people have a tendency to get wild and kick up their heels,'' <PERSON> Vicki </PERSON> said. `` It gets depressing.'' `` You get a different breed of people,'' said <PERSON> Dale </PERSON>. `` Those who do n't like society go to those type places. It's kind of the end of the road.'' The two also had to contend with bears while mining along the <ORGANIZATION> Alaska-Canada </ORGANIZATION> border. `` We were pretty heavily armed at the mine because they would surprise you or you would surprise them,'' <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> said in an interview. `` You'd be in a bind without a weapon. They destroyed our camp a couple of times. One time they walked through a camper-trailer by going in one end and tearing out the whole wall and destroying the inside. They pushed a refrigerator through the wall and made another hole to go out.'' They mined from 1973 until the mid-1980s, always on the lookout for thieves. `` One guy took a chain saw and stole the floor out of a cabin,'' <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> said. The two, both born and raised in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, compared the mining business to the entertainment field. `` Some years were good and some were not very good at all,'' <PERSON> Vicki </PERSON> said. `` I would n't recommend it for someone who needs security. It's like the music industry. You ca n't count on anything. You work your hardest and hope it works out at the end.'' They recently signed a recording contract with <ORGANIZATION> Airborne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION>, a new independent label in <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, an Airborne vice president, had heard them sing several years ago while he was a concert promoter in <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION>. `` One listen and I was sold on their music,'' <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> recalled about his first exposure to them. `` I decided then that if I ever had a label, they would be on it.'' Their first single record is `` You Fit Right Into My Heart.'' Their sound is sure to draw comparisons to the Carpenters, a brother-sister duo who had hits 15 years ago with `` For All We Know,'' `` Superstar'' and `` Rainy Days & amp; Mondays.'' `` We listen to them,'' <PERSON> Vicki </PERSON> said. `` But our style of harmony does n't resemble theirs in any way, only that we are brother and sister. We do have kind of a folk influence which they did also.'' `` Our music is kind of on the sweet side but ours is not as sweet as theirs. Ours is more country,'' <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> said. `` We've got a new sound with a different approach. We do n't sound like anyone else. Our music is easy to listen to, positive, straight ahead.'' The Sanders are the latest in a variety of family acts in country music, joining <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gatlin </PERSON> and the <LOCATION> Gatlin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brothers </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Judds </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- mother and daughter -RRB-, the Forester Sisters, the Whites -LRB- father and daughters -RRB- and others. `` The blend you get when you put family together is going to be closer than if you are not related,'' said <PERSON> Vicki </PERSON>, who has two other brothers. `` And you make more concessions when working with family on the road. You have disagreements but you forgive your brother or sister. It's harder to forgive someone not related.'' Said <PERSON> Dale </PERSON>, `` A lot of families grow up singing and just fall into it.''
</TEXT>
