<FIRST>r f PM-LuxuryCars-Future     07-19 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Luxury Cars-Future,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>Analyst: Domestic Luxury Marques Threatened by Boring Image, New
Imports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Makers of domestic luxury sedans, already plagued by a dwindling, aging buyer base and a dull product image, likely will lose market share in the next five years to foreign luxury marques slated to enter the domestic market, according to industry consultant <PERSON> J.D </PERSON>. Power. In an interview Monday, <PERSON> Power </PERSON> described a December survey of 2,100 luxury-car owners designed to identify the image of 22 luxury marques, including four not yet sold in this country. Image itself is a vague concept of the general perception of a car including its advertising, styling, handling and performance and intangibles such as elegance. <PERSON> Power </PERSON> said the survey revealed a surprising lack of distinctive image among many luxury names; those surveyed recognized only an average of 2.7 marques, including the one they purchased within the 18 to 24 months before the survey was taken. Some luxury cars do have a clear image. <ORGANIZATION> Mercedes-Benz </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION> particularly are considered elegant, prestigious, enjoyable to drive, well-engineered, contemporary but classically styled and distinctive, <PERSON> Power </PERSON> said. But domestic makes overall are seen as conservative, comfortable and unexciting, he said. That is despite individual successes such as <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> division, which has attracted more younger, import-oriented buyers while <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Cadillac </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Buick </ORGANIZATION> and Oldsmobile have not <PERSON> Power </PERSON> said image-building is a lengthy and costly process, and may lag behind a marque's actual sales, as with <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON>. But he said all domestic makers of luxury sedans likely will lose market share in the next five years to new entries such as <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION>'s Infiniti and <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION>'s Lexus line, both from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, and, possibly to <ORGANIZATION> Citroen </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Opel </ORGANIZATION> from <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The luxury car market in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> peaked in 1986 with sales of 1.176 million. Power predicted a downturn to 1 million in sales this year, followed by a drop to 969,000 in 1989 and a recovery to 1.186 million sales by 1993. The luxury market's recovery will be fueled partly by the entry of the new marques, he said. Infiniti and Lexus plan to offer six - and eight-cylinder engine coupes and sedans and <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION>'s Acura luxury line plans a sedan with an eight-cylinder engine, moving steadily in the arena dominated by the Big Three, <PERSON> Power </PERSON> said The new entries will find it easier to create solid, distinctive images for their products because of their specialization and a lack of the poor-quality and look-alike problems that marred domestic nameplates such as <ORGANIZATION> Buick </ORGANIZATION> and Oldsmobile, <PERSON> Power </PERSON> said. Also, while 56 percent of luxury owners age 65 or older said they shop only for domestic models, only 6 percent of buyers younger than 35 said they would not consider imports. And 43 percent of those younger buyers said they did not consider domestic cars at all. As the younger buyers age and move further into the luxury car market, the Big Three will be forced to design with them in mind and move their luxury-marque images in their direction if they hope to lure them away from Japanese and European dealers, <PERSON> Power </PERSON> said. In addition to <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON>'s success, Big Three makers have begun improving and modernizing their images by offering sportier two-seat models such as the <ORGANIZATION> Cadillac </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Allante </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Buick </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reatta </ORGANIZATION> and the much-delayed <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> Turbo Coupe by <PERSON> Maserati </PERSON>. European makers will not be similarly threatened as long as they continue moving their cars upward in price and exclusivity, thus protecting their images, he said.
</TEXT>
