<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Stocks Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stock prices fell slightly Tuesday as the market braced itself for another possible rise in British interest rates. The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index was 2.8 points, or 0.2 percent, lower at 1,846.5 at midday. Trading volume registered a modest 271.2 million shares, compared with 219.5 million shares at the same time Monday. Dealers remained unconvinced that Monday's half-point rise in the British commercial banks' base lending rate to 10.5 percent would be sufficient to dampen inflationary pressures in the economy. However, the pound was able to recover some lost ground which diffused the immediate need for interest rate hikes, dealers said. Reported heavy central bank intervention to cap the dollar's rise, combined with the effects of Monday's sixth rise in interest rates in as many weeks, also helped buoy sterling against other currencies, market watchers said However, amid uncertainty about the near-term direction of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> equities, buyers were only interested in selected stocks, dealers said.
