<HEAD>Pac Bell Proposes Giving up Monopoly on Local Calls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION>, breaking from tradition, has made a surprise proposal to give up its monopoly on local toll calls in exchange for reduced state regulation. The giant local phone company called its proposal `` the most significant change since the breakup of the Bell System in 1984.'' Under the offer, the company would also expand the local toll-free zone and offer push-button phones without extra charge in exchange for the decreased regulation. If approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utilities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, the plan would give customers access to high-technology, low-cost services. Consumer representatives greeted the proposal with trepidation. `` My biggest fear is that we will have the pretense of competition but not the safeguards of competition,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gnaizda </PERSON>, a lawyer who represents six minority and low-income groups in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bell </LOCATION> rate case before the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utilities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. Others would compete in handling local toll calls, but `` there wo n't be any real competition'' and `` the company will escape effective public and <ORGANIZATION> PUC </ORGANIZATION> scrutiny,'' <PERSON> Gnaizda </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION>'s profit will exceed $ 1 billion this year, more than twice its highest level before deregulation, he said The <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utilities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which has suggested increasing phone company flexibility in the new market created by the dismemberment of the Bell system, will consider all the proposals during the next year. According to <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION>, the new proposal is more generous than a plan the company presented in January in an attempt to loosen state regulation. The <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utilities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> would continue to approve residential rates after 1992, but without the exhaustive, three-year inquiry of <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bell </LOCATION>'s financial structure. Under the plan, regulatory controls would also be loosened to allow new services to be introduced more quickly. Monthly business rates would be allowed to rise gradually to approach the cost of service. However, rates on premium residential services such as call-forwarding, call-waiting and speed-dialing would be cut. <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> said it also would expect reduced local toll rates because of competition.
