<HEAD>Oil Prices Surge; Grain, Soybean Futures Plummet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs with oil prices, picks up 5th graf pvs,
Soybeans for</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Housing construction partially recovered in June, rising 5.1 percent after plummeting 12.6 percent in May, the government said today. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the increase in housing starts was the steepest in four months. Mortgage rates eased in June, contributing to the revival. On Monday, reports of a possible cease-fire in the Iran-Iraq war sent oil prices soaring, while grain and soybean futures plunged following heavy weekend rains in the drought-stricken <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the August contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the benchmark <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil, shot up 84 cents a barrel Monday to settle at $ 15.70 a barrel. It was the biggest rise since a jump of $ 1.01 a barrel on April 11. But prices retreated in early trading today. The August contract for <ORGANIZATION> WTI </ORGANIZATION> fell 30 cents to $ 15.40 a barrel. Soybeans for July delivery skidded more than $ 1.09 a bushel, one of the steepest one-day soybean price declines in the history of the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>. July corn plunged 30 cents a bushel. The spike in oil prices reignited inflation worries on Wall Street and in the credit markets. The concerns were heightened by a <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> report that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industry in June operated at 83.1 percent of capacity _ its highest point in eight years and edging closer to a level that economists believe signals a pickup in inflation. The nervousness about inflation weakened stock prices. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 23.30 points last week, dropped 11.56 to 2,117.89. Bond prices also fell, forcing interest rates higher. The yield on the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s closely watched 30-year bond jumped to 9.23 percent from 9.14 percent late Friday. The possibility of a breakthrough in the 8-year-old Iran-Iraq conflict, along with aggressive dollar sales by central banks, pushed the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency to a weaker finish against most key foreign currencies. The dollar historically is regarded as a safe-haven currency during times of unrest, and the prospect of peace between the two <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> enemies spurred investors to sell dollars. The news of a possible cease-fire between <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> alao raised prospects that the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> would be able to calm its chronic infighting, which has led to overproduction of oil and lower prices. The ensuing price jump in the futures market brought oil back to its levels of earlier this month, before a steep skid in prices sparked by concerns about a worldwide oversupply of oil. Analysts said prices were driven up by traders who had been betting on further declines in prices and rushed to cover their positions by buying contracts. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> said Monday it would accept a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> resolution calling for an immediate cease-fire in its war with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. However, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> also said it will not withdraw its troops from its borders and called on Iranians to prepare to thwart further Iraqi attacks. Supporting the price rebound was a report that <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s pricing committee would meet within the next 30 days.
