<HEAD>Swiss Army Knives: Made Abroad, Marketed By Connecticut Company</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEAN GOLEMBESKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHELTON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Swiss </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> knife is one of those products that keeps finding a new market _ from GIs in the foxhole to yuppie campers on a weekend in the wild. And that's good news for a small <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> company that had the good sense to promote the handy pocket tool from forgotten sideline to bestseller. The story of how the <ORGANIZATION> Forschner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <PERSON> Shelton </PERSON> came to be the exclusive <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> marketer of <ORGANIZATION> Swiss </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> knives is a classic tale of serendipity. The company's founders picked up the knife in a search for good European cutlery for butchers. Years later, new owners would move the little red-handled knives to the top of the line. <ORGANIZATION> Forschner </ORGANIZATION> sold more than 4 million of the knives in 1987 alone, accounting for more than half the company's sales. `` It's a good business,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Forschner </ORGANIZATION>'s 37-year-old president and chief executive officer The knives, manufactured by the <ORGANIZATION> Victorinox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cutlery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, are readily identified by their color and many gadgets. The most popular model, with about 500,000 units sold in 1987, is the Classic, a key chain model that has, in addition to a knife blade, a nail file, scissors, tweezers and a toothpick. The latest addition to the more than 60 different models is the SwissChamp, which was introduced this year. It has 29 features, including a ballpoint pen, pliers, wood saw, fish scaler, corkscrew and magnifying glass. The typical customer is a man between the ages of 21 to 35 living in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> or <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said. The weakest sales for the knives are in the Southeast. The company, whose stock is publicly traded, had record sales of more than $ 36.4 million in 1987, up 24 percent from 1986. After expenses, the company earned about $ 1.8 million. The previous record was set in 1986, when <ORGANIZATION> Forschner </ORGANIZATION> rang up $ 27.3 million in sales. The <ORGANIZATION> Swiss </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> knives _ which range in price from $ 8 to $ 18 for the Classic to $ 90 for the SwissChamp _ accounted for roughly $ 20 million of last year's sales. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> snapped up about 35 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Victorinox </ORGANIZATION>'s output of <ORGANIZATION> Swiss </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> knives in 1987 The sales have continued upward despite a more than doubling of the effective price of the knives in the past two years due to the declining value of the dollar, <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said. Americans got their first exposure to the knives following World War II, when GIs were stationed in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said GIs `` gave the name <ORGANIZATION> Swiss </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> knife to the product ... because everyone in the <ORGANIZATION> Swiss </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> carried it.'' The <ORGANIZATION> R.H. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forschner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> started in 1855 as a manufacturer of butcher scales in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn </LOCATION>. Sometime during the 1880s, it moved to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, where it remained until relocating to <PERSON> Shelton </PERSON> in 1976. It currently employs 80 people at its headquarters and a <LOCATION> Shelton </LOCATION> warehouse, where it does some assembly and repairs. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, who started with the company in sales in 1975, was named president and chief operating officer in June 1987. He assumed the new title of chief executive officer this March. `` The company after World War I started importing knives from <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, because they were selling scales to the meat-packing industry. So, therefore, they could assume the same people would buy knives,'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said. `` World War II came along and their German source was naturally unavailable. ... When the war ended, the grandson of the founder went over to <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> because <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> was devastated and found this little company called <ORGANIZATION> Victorinox </ORGANIZATION> that made very good butcher knives and he started importing them,'' he continued. The Swiss Army knife, also made at the Swiss factory, was tossed in for good measure. In 1957, the founding family sold <ORGANIZATION> R.H. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forschner </ORGANIZATION> to a businessman who expanded the butcher knife segment and phased out the scale business. In 1974, the business was sold again, this time to <ORGANIZATION> Marline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Inc. of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> <PERSON> Marline </PERSON> took the company public in 1983. `` The business was purchased for the butcher knife business. And lo and behold, sitting there in the corner was the litte <ORGANIZATION> Swiss </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> knife,'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said. `` We did a market research study of the whole company, and the market research study indicated that we had a great opportunity with the <ORGANIZATION> Swiss </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> knife.'' The company turned up its marketing program for the knives in 1976 when it introduced sealed display cases, which are now used by 10,000 retailers to show off 10 to 20 knives. `` It was a very successful program,'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said. `` It made it a silent salesman. It's always there in the store. And frankly, ... you do n't get up in the morning and say, ` I'm going to go out and buy a <ORGANIZATION> Swiss </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> knife.' It's something you know about and if you see it in a store, it reminds you, ` Hey I will want one of those.'''
</TEXT>
