<HEAD>Posts 31.6 Percent Profit Gain for 2nd Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Companies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday its second-quarter profit climbed 31.6 percent from a year earlier, as its cigarette, food and brewing businesses each posted revenue gains. The company said its after-tax profit rose to $ 627 million, or $ 2.68 a share, in the three months ended June 30, compared with earnings of $ 476 million, or $ 2 a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 10 percent to $ 7.8 billion from $ 7.1 billion. For the first six months of the year, <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION>'s earnings rose 30.9 pecent to $ 1.13 billion, or $ 4.80 a share, from $ 862 million, or $ 3.62 a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 10.2 percent to $ 15.1 billion from $ 13.7 billion. <PERSON> Hamish </PERSON> <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive, said domestic cigarette revenue and unit volume each rose and the company expanded its market share in the quarter and first half. Among its cigarette brands are Marlboro, <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Slims </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Benson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Hedges </PERSON> and Merit. He said the company's <ORGANIZATION> Miller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewing </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary had higher operating revenue on higher barrel volume for both the quarter and the half. Unit volume and revenue also grew at the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foods </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> division, while the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foods </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Worldwide </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coffee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> business had higher revenue on slightly lower volume. The company said volume growth was especially strong at the <ORGANIZATION> Oscar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mayer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foods </ORGANIZATION> division, as both <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayer </PERSON> brand meats and <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> turkey products expanded their market shares.
