<FIRST>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv19   07-19 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 19,0613</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Tuesday July 19</NOTE>
<HEAD>It's How You Look at It</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Is it a sign of great weakness that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> owed $ 368 billion to foreign creditors at the end of 1987, more than was owed by any other nation? Or is it a sign of strength? The popular position is that the `` debt'' is further evidence of a decline of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, it is said, is the world's largest debtor nation, the insinuation being that debt is bad. In this instance, however, the debt referred to can also be viewed as strength. There is even a school of thought that declines to call it debt, pointing out instead that much of the money is invested. They ask you to consider this simple equivalent: When you put $ 20,000 into a $ 100,000 house for your family do you explain to your friends that you have just gone deeply into debt, or do you tell them you've just made the best investment of your life? Most people would say the $ 20,000 was invested. And so would any foreigner who put money into <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> stocks, bonds and real estate. Such folks invest for a good return. They do n't see themselves as lenders. They really are n't. The popular view of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> being the largest debtor nation comes from a comparison of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> investments abroad vs. foreign investments in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. It is true: Foreigners invest more here than we do there. Do they do so because they lack faith? Or because of the attractiveness of American investments? Does it indicate an Uncle <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> with his hand out? Or foreigners eager to get in on good investments? In short, is it debt, or is it investment? Is it weakness _ or strength? While those who call it debt are entitled to do so, others point out that if foreigners buy stock in a company, put money in an American bank, buy <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government securities or purchase a production plant, they are investing. It makes sense. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market is the world's biggest by far. The country is also the most politically stable, a factor that has dictated investments as far back as international trade itself. And <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> investments are inexpensive. It is the latter factor, a direct result of the decline of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar, that has been the latest spur to foreign investments in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sanford </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York-based </LOCATION> broker who has arranged at least 70 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> investments for British companies, offers some succinct reasons for the phenomenon. Despite belonging to the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, he says, the British have an island economy. It is a mature economy in which successful companies long ago carved out their niches. The result: `` They butt heads in a small market.'' They look for ways to expand, especially if they have good cash flow, and they see the biggest market of all in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> _ growing, evolving, changing and, to boot, English-speaking. English laws discourage dividend distributions, a situation that produces problems for good companies. They must expand, and what better place to do so than in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> where, because of the devalued dollar, businesses are available at a discount? There is another side of the coin. If the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> economy is so attractive to foreigners, why should n't it be equally so to Americans? That is, why should they have to send their money abroad?
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Tues July 19</NOTE>
