<TEXT>
 A major Japanese auto parts manufacturer announced Tuesday it will set up a new plant in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to manufacture and sell auto parts to domestic and Japanese car makers in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kogyo </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, based in southwestern <LOCATION> Kawasaki </LOCATION>, said <LOCATION> PK </LOCATION> <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION> will be located in <LOCATION> Shelbyville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> PK </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> will be owned 75 percent by <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kogyo </ORGANIZATION> and the remaining 25 percent by <ORGANIZATION> Mitsui </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a Japanese trading company, company spokesman <PERSON> Mitsuru </PERSON> <PERSON> Kataoka </PERSON> said. The plant, which will begin operating by the end of 1989, will hire about 155 employees, the spokesman said. The manufactured car parts will include metal and plastic parts for use in passenger cars and trucks, he said.
