<HEAD>Stocks Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prices fell Tuesday in a quiet session on the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> as the market digested Monday's half-point rise in the British commercial banks' base lending rate. The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index dropped 4.5 points, or 0.2 percent, to close at 1,844.8. Volume rose to a moderate 447.7 million shares, compared with Monday's 366.4 million shares. Dealers said British equities ignored developments on Wall Street until about the last hour of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> dealings, when a key market indicator in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> abruptly fell about 15 points. The Dow Jones industrial average was off 14.94 at 2,102.95 as <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> trading ended. Players were still preoccupied by concerns that Monday's half-point rise in the British commercial banks' base rates to 10.5 percent would be insufficient to curb inflation, dealers said However, sterling rose on the foreign exchange markets, diffusing the immediate need for an interest rate hike, dealers said. Meanwhile, amid uncertainty about the near-term direction for <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> equities, buyers were only interested in selected stocks, dealers said.
