 Stock prices held at sharply lower levels today as computerized sell programs kicked in and took their toll on equities. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was off 29.87 points at 2,088.02 by mid-afternoon. Declining issues outnumbered advances by more than 2 to 1 in nationwide trading of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> Exchange-listed stocks, with 453 up, 970 down and 461 unchanged. Volume on the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> came to 105.59 million shares as of 2 p.m. on Wall Street. The Dow average moved up about 2 points in the first half hour of trading but sank below the psychologically important 2,100 level at midday and then continued to fall despite continued reports of higher corporate earnings for the second quarter. <PERSON> Hildegarde </PERSON> <PERSON> Zagorski </PERSON>, a second vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, noted that the decline began in the technology sector, where several stocks tumbled. `` That started the ball rolling, and then we got the sell programs.'' Other analysts remarked on a sense of apathy among investors. `` The primary problem is the mood of the market,'' said <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldman </PERSON>, a vice president at <ORGANIZATION> A.G. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Edwards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sons </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>. `` I'm very disappointed with today's action. There's a worldwide malaise about owning equities.'' <PERSON> Goldman </PERSON> noted that despite relatively favorable fundamentals such as lower interest rates and higher corporate earnings, `` the vast majority of investors are in a very apathetic mood ... they're not coming to the equities trough. Earlier in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the key Nikkei 225-share index plummeted more than 500 points to its lowest level this year. <PERSON> Zagorski </PERSON> attributed the decline in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to inflation fears sparked by higher oil prices, which rose on Monday following reports that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> had acceded to a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> resolution calling for a cease-fire in its war against <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. But reports that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> downed three Iraqi jets today cast a veil of confusion over prospects for a cease-fire. Among technology issues, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> was off 1 ~ at 123 The company introduced new computers and personal computer software. Tandem fell -RCB- to 18 \; the company faces a new challenge from <ORGANIZATION> Digital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION> in the transaction processing business Among other actively traded <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> issues, <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carbide </ORGANIZATION> was down 1 at 24 \; <ORGANIZATION> Interco </ORGANIZATION> was up 3 -LRB- at 57 -LCB-; and <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> was off ~ at 45 -RRB- The <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>'s composite index of all its listed common stocks fell 1.67 to 151.16. At the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the market value index was off 1.03 at 308.05.
