<HEAD>Coca-Cola Enterprises Earnings Up 16.9 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the bottler spawned by <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said Tuesday its profit rose 16.9 percent in the second quarter on an 18.3 percent gain in revenue. The Atlanta-based company attributed the gains to increased volume, improved operating effiencies and the inclusion of recently acquired bottling companies in the results. The company was formed in 1986 out of Coca-Cola-owned bottling operations and is 49 percent owned by <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION> said its volume in cases rose about 22 percent in the second quarter and 19 percent in the first half, largely because of acquisitions If all acquisitions of bottling operations in 1987 and 1988 had occurred at the beginning of 1987, volume would have increased about 9 percent in the second quarter and 6 percent for the six-month period. The company issued $ 250 million in preferred stock during the second quarter. Because of the dividend payments on that, net income available to common shareholders rose 11.4 percent, less than the overall rise in net income. Net income rose to $ 41.0 million in the second quarter from $ 35.1 million. Net income available to common shareholders rose to $ 39.1 million, or 28 cents a share, from $ 35.1 million. Revenue rose to $ 1.10 billion from $ 929 million in the second quarter and rose 16.8 percent to $ 1.95 billion from $ 1.67 billion in the first half.
