<HEAD>Aerospace Firm Posts Profit of $21.9 Million in 2nd Qtr.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> posted a profit Tuesday of $ 21.9 million in the second quarter, compared to a $ 15.4 million loss a year earlier, when the company took a large write-off on a secret project believed to be the Stealth bomber. The aerospace company reported that its sales for the quarter fell 5.2 percent to $ 1.35 billion from $ 1.42 billion in the second quarter of 1987. In the first six months of the year, <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION>'s profit climbed to $ 161.5 million, or $ 3.44 a share, compared with $ 25.2 million, or 54 cents a share, a year earlier. Six-month revenue fell 4 percent to $ 2.71 billion from $ 2.83 billion a year earlier. The company attributed the improved second-quarter results to absence of a $ 124.3 million write-off it took in the second quarter of 1987 on a project it has n't officially identified, but which is widely believed to be the B-2, or Stealth bomber. Earlier this year, <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> acknowledged for the first time the company is developing the bomber, which is designed to be difficult to detect on enemy radar. Second-quarter operating profit was cut by lower revenues on the unnamed classified program, as well as by reduced sales and lower profit margins on guidance units for the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>'s MX missile and other military projects. Revenue also was reduced because of a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> policy that requires contractors to pay a larger share of research and development costs that they previously did, the company said. Production of inertial measurement units for the MX has lagged behind schedule, but the company says it now is producing the units on a schedule acceptable to the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>. The government is withholding less than $ 50 million in progress payments on the MX systems, down from a high of $ 145 million in December 1987, <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> is one of three <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> aerospace companies whose offices were searched last month in the nationwide investigation of allegations that defense industry consultants bribed <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials for information to help win contracts. The company has said it is cooperating in the probe, which so far has centered on independent industry consultants and former <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials.
