<HEAD>Citicorp, Wells Fargo, Mellon, Irving Post 2nd-Quarter Profit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Four of the nation's largest banking companies on Tuesday reported profits in the second quarter in contrast with steep losses a year earlier. <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Wells </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fargo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Mellon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Irving </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> noted that the second-quarter losses in 1987 stemmed from additions to loan reserves for potentially uncollectible loans to developing countries. <ORGANIZATION> Great </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, one of the biggest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> thrifts, said its second-quarter earnings jumped 22 percent _ to $ 64.7 million, or 50 cents a share, from $ 53 million, or 40 cents a share, a year earlier. New York-based <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest bank holding company, said it earned $ 359 million, or $ 1.03 a share, compared with a loss of $ 2.6 billion in the second quarter of last year. If the loan-loss provisions had n't been made, <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION> said, it would have earned $ 285 million, or 93 cents a share, in the second quarter of 1987. <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION> attributed the improvement in the latest quarter to continued strength in its core banking businesses in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and abroad. Much of the momentum in banking came from <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION>'s credit card business, the company said. The banking giant also credited positive results from securities and currency trading during the quarter, as well as gains from venture capital loans. In the first half of the year, <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION> posted net profit of $ 717 million, or $ 2.04 a share, compared with a net loss of $ 2.3 billion in the first six months of 1987. San Francisco-based <ORGANIZATION> Wells </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fargo </ORGANIZATION>, the 11th-largest <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> company </ORGANIZATION>, reported second-quarter earnings of $ 124.4 million, or $ 2.24 a share, compared with a net loss of $ 293.7 million a year earlier. Excluding the provision for risky loans, <ORGANIZATION> Wells </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fargo </ORGANIZATION> would have earned $ 83.6 million, or $ 1.45 a share, in the second quarter of last year. The company said an increase in net interest income, resulting from favorable market conditions in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, was a major factor in the second-quarter improvement. <PERSON> Wells </PERSON> <PERSON> Fargo </PERSON>, which acquired <ORGANIZATION> Barclays </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> in May, is the third-largest banking company in the state. In the first half of the year, the bank posted net profit of $ 244.8 million, or $ 4.39 a share, compared with a net loss of $ 215.4 million a year earlier. <PERSON> Mellon </PERSON>, based in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> and the 16th-biggest bank company, posted net income for the latest quarter of $ 28 million, or 75 cents a share, as opposed to a net loss of $ 566 million a year earlier. For the first six months of the year, <ORGANIZATION> Mellon </ORGANIZATION> earned $ 53 million, or $ 1.40 a share, compared with a net loss of $ 626 million in the 1987 half. New York-based Irving, the 24th-largest bank company and the long-time target of a hostile takeover bid from <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said it earned a record $ 169.9 million, or $ 8.85 a share, compared with a net loss of $ 142 million in the second quarter of 1987. In the first half, <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> had net income of $ 222.3 million, or $ 11.56 a share, compared with a net loss of $ 113.4 million a year earlier. Great Western Financial, based in <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, said the 22 percent rise in its second-quarter earnings reflected solid performances by each of its core businesses, including continued growth in lending. By contrast, earnings in the first half fell 14.8 percent _ to $ 121 million, or 95 cents a share, from $ 142 million, or $ 1.11 a share, a year earlier. The company said its results benefitted from exceptionally strong gains from sales of home mortgage loans in the first six months of 1987.
