<HEAD>Profit Up 12 Percent in Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> McGraw-Hill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> reported Tuesday that its profit rose 12 percent in the second quarter from a year earlier, boosted by increased revenue from all its operating companies. The diversified publisher said its net income increased to $ 44.8 million, or 92 cents a share, in the latest three months from $ 40 million, or 79 cents a share, in the second quarter of last year. Second-quarter revenue rose 4.2 percent, to $ 443.7 million from $ 425.9 million a year earlier. Results for the latest quarter include the sale of the company's 49 percent interest in <LOCATION> Nikkei-McGraw-Hill </LOCATION>, a joint venture publishing company in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, for $ 283.1 million The gain on the sale was $ 109.8 million after taxes. <ORGANIZATION> McGraw-Hill </ORGANIZATION> said it also took previously announced asset writedowns and other unusual charges in the second quarter totaling $ 107.6 million after taxes. `` All of our operating companies produced revenue increases in the second quarter,'' said Chairman <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dionne </PERSON>. As of July 1, <ORGANIZATION> McGraw-Hill </ORGANIZATION> was restructured into three operating companies: publishing, financial services and information services. For the first half of the year, earnings rose 14.9 percent _ to $ 71.8 million, or $ 1.48 a share, from $ 62.5 million, or $ 1.23 a share, a year earlier. First-half revenue was up 5.3 percent, to $ 839.3 million from $ 797.4 million.
