<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0615</SECOND>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The stock market skidded lower Tuesday as investor nervousness over the direction of interest rates overrode a flurry of favorable corporate earnings reports. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which fell more than 11 points on Monday, dropped another 20.63 to close at 2,097.26. Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 9 to 5 in nationwide trading of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> Exchange-listed stocks, with 517 issues up, 918 down and 492 unchanged. Volume on the floor of the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> was 144.11 million shares, down from 156.21 million in Monday's session. Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trading at regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter market, totaled 168.11 million shares. Stock prices were mixed at the opening of trading but soon headed lower. By midday the Dow sank below the psychologically important 2,100 mark and continued to hold at depressed levels despite repeated reports of higher corporate earnings for the second quarter. <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, a senior vice president at <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Albany </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, noted that higher interest rates overseas coupled with fear that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> may also hike rates in this country `` is the principal reason making the market nervous.'' He said the market largely discounted repeated double-digit corporate earnings increases for fear `` they will be neutralized by higher interest rates ... down the road.'' The technology sector, which typically has been a leader in propelling the market to higher levels, was particularly weak. `` It can be a little depressing -LRB- elsewhere in the market -RRB- when you see that group give ground,'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. With the technology sector down, computer-driven sell programs kicked in and further depressed stock prices. Noting that the market is continuing to lose momentum, some analysts remarked on a sense of apathy among investors and a mood that is negative toward equities. <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Peroni </PERSON>, a technical analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Janney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Montgomery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scott </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, said investors `` are hesitant to hold on amid even the slightest weakness, rather than ride a correction through.'' He attributed the `` near-sighted behavior'' to residual trauma from last October's stock crash. Earlier in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the key Nikkei 225-share index plummeted more than 500 points to its lowest level this year. But because the drop largely was a reaction to Monday's sharply higher oil prices, traders said it did not take a toll on domestic trading. Among technology issues, <ORGANIZATION> Seagate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> plunged 5 -LCB- to 13 following a sharply lower earnings report. It was the most active issue in over-the-counter trading, and one trader said <ORGANIZATION> Seagate </ORGANIZATION>'s decline affected other companies in the industry because it provides parts to other computer makers Elsewhere in the technology sector, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>, which introduced new computers and personal software Tuesday, fell 1 -RRB- at 124; <ORGANIZATION> NCR </ORGANIZATION> fell 3 -RRB- to 58 \; Prime Computer was off \ at 15 and National Semiconductor was off \ at 11 Among other actively traded <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> issues, <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carbide </ORGANIZATION> was down -RCB- at 24 -LCB-; <ORGANIZATION> Interco </ORGANIZATION> was up 4 at 58 -RRB-; <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> was off | at 45 |, and <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </O