<HEAD>Corn, Soybean Futures Plunge Again As Rain Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Rainy weather brought another sharp drop in corn and soybean futures prices Tuesday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> and some analysts wondered if the Midwestern drought had finally been quenched. On other markets, silver futures soared to a 10-month high; energy futures fell; livestock and meat were mostly lower; and stock-index futures retreated. The wet-weather pattern that drenched parts of the upper <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> over the weekend brought rain on Tuesday to the region's parched southern and western portions. More rain was expected in the northern Corn Belt on Wednesday. Analysts said the rain halted further deterioration of the badly damaged corn crop and greatly improved the yield prospects for soybeans, which are just entering the critical pod-forming stage. Some corn and soybean contracts plummeted their permissible limits in reaction to the rain, and analysts said that after two consecutive days of limit losses, the markets appeared to have discounted all the rain in sight for the Corn Belt. `` I think we'll have a two-sided trade tomorrow,'' said <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Lespinasse </PERSON>, a trader with <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` We'll probably open lower but not necessarily.'' <PERSON> Lespinasse </PERSON> said the weather would continue set the market's course and <PERSON> Cathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Leow </PERSON>, an assistant vice president with <ORGANIZATION> Thomson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> McKinnon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, agreed `` Last week a lot of people bought soybeans at $ 9 thinking they were going to go to $ 13,'' she said. `` Now they're thinking, ` My god, what if we continue to get rain?'. `` It could be that the drought's broken,'' Ms. <PERSON> Leow </PERSON> said. `` Sure, we need 10 to 15 inches of rain in most areas to bring the soil moisture back to normal ... but at least we're not seeing further deterioration in the crops.'' Although it was uncertain how much rain the western Corn Belt would receive overnight, Ms. <PERSON> Leow </PERSON> said the price drop of the last two days probably had taken a substantial rainfall into account. Oat futures also finished lower but wheat futures advanced on expectations of new export business, analysts said. Wheat settled 6 cents to 8 -LCB- cents higher with the contract for delivery in July at $ 3.76 a bushel; corn was the limit 15 cents lower to 5 cents higher with July at $ 3.08 -LCB- a bushel; oats were 14 cents lower to 3 cents higher with July at $ 2.90 a bushel; soybeans were 6 cents to the limit 45 cents lower with July at $ 8.74 -LCB- a bushel. The price for July delivery of silver soared more than 57 cents on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> to $ 7.727, the highest price for near-month delivery since Sept. 10, when the September contract closed at $ 8. Analysts cited a number of factors for the rise, including the two-day old Peruvian silver miners' strike and growing investment demand for silver as a hedge against inflation. World supplies of silver are plentiful and the strike in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, which accounts for about 20 percent of world production, normally would have little long-term effect on prices, said <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Demler </PERSON>, metals analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` If investment demand were not picking up, the fact that the supply is being disrupted from <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> would not have a large impact'' on the supply-demand scenario, he said. A bullish technical picture also spurred buying of silver, which helped boost prices of other precious metals, other analysts said. Gold settled $ 8.70 to $ 9.80 higher with August at $ 447.50 a troy ounce; silver was 57.7 cents to 62.5 cents higher with July at $ 7.727 a troy ounce. Oil futures prices retreated on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> as traders grew skeptical that a possible cease-fire in the Iran-Iraq war would soon reduce the world oversupply of oil, analysts said. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 7 cents to 47 cents lower with August at $ 15.23 a barrel; heating oil was .37 cent to .65 cent lower with August at 42.90 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .46 cent lower to .15 cent higher with August at 50.65 cents a gallon. Lower cash values pressured cattle futures prices on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> while pork futures fell on expectations of weakening cash prices, analysts said. Live cattle were 1.18 cents lower to .23 cent higher with August at 63.87 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .68 cent lower with August at 76.10 cents a pound; hogs were .80 cent lower to .48 cent higher with July at 46.65 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .70 cent to 1.20 cents lower with July at 35.85 cents a pound. The contract for September delivery of the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500 stock index settled 1.85 points lower at 270.45 on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>.
