<HEAD>U.S. To Participate in Short-Term Loan to Brazil</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday it had agreed to participate in a $ 500 million, short-term bridge loan to <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Settlements </ORGANIZATION>, an organization in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> of the world's central banks, also is participating, the department said in a statement. A <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> participation would amount to about half of the loan, which must be repaid by Dec. 30. It is intended to tide <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> over until an <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> loan is disbursed later this year. <PERSON> Mailson </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferreira </PERSON> <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Nobrega </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s finance minister, recently told bankers in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> that this month his country will pay foreign commercial banks the interest it owes them for June and July, bringing it up to date for interest due from the beginning of the year. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and a committee of its major creditor banks reached an agreement last month to end a moratorium on interest payments begun by <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> in February 1987. The agreement calls for the rescheduling of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s $ 62 billion debt to foreign banks and the issuing of $ 5.2 billion in new loans. The nation's total foreign debt of $ 120 billion is the biggest in the developing world. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> also is taking steps to restrain inflation and curtail its government deficit. `` <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> participation in this multilateral effort indicates our strong support for <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s economic reform efforts,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> statement said.
