<HEAD>Honeywell Posts 41.8 Percent Profit Drop In Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday posted a 41.8 percent drop in its second quarter profit from a year earlier, due mainly to $ 43 million in one-time charges and to accounting changes. <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> said its net income fell to $ 31.6 million, or 75 cents a share, from $ 54.3 million, or $ 1.21 a share, in second quarter 1987. Sales in the three months ended July 3 rose to $ 1.75 billion from $ 1.57 billion a year earlier. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Renier </PERSON>, president and chief executive officer of the defense contractor and maker of building controls, said quarterly results reflected a $ 27 million after-tax charge related to cost overruns on fixed-price contracts in the military avionics group and a $ 16 million charge to cover losses in a semiconductor product line. The military avionics group also suffered a reduced asset value under more stringent accounting rules, said <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Eich </PERSON>, a company spokeswoman. `` With the exception of the previously announced charges in our military avionics group, performance in our other major businesses remains strong, with increases in both sales and operating profit,'' <PERSON> Renier </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Renier </PERSON> said operating profit was up in the following divisions: industrial automation and control, defense and marine systems, home and building automation and control, and international business. Six-month net income was $ 89.3 million, or $ 2.11 a share, down from $ 98.0 million, or $ 2.17 a year ago. Total sales for the first half of 1988 were $ 3.48 billion, compared with $ 3.05 billion in 1987.
