<HEAD>China Creates New Bureau to Oversee Quality</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has set up a new state bureau to oversee efforts to reduce the number of shoddy, substandard goods on the market and help Chinese products meet international quality standards, an official daily said Wednesday. State Councillor Song <PERSON> Jian </PERSON> said Tuesday the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supervision </ORGANIZATION> would strengthen supervision over technology and establish an authoritative system of standardization and measurement, the <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> Daily said. The bureau will manage and adjust national standards on production, development, distribution and consumption. Song said the country must actively adopt international standards and a system of international quality authentication to make Chinese goods more competitive on world markets. He said that since <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> initiated its economic reforms and open-door trade policy in 1979, the country has put into effect more than 11,000 state standards and 500 measurement regulations. But he said substandard products remain a serious problem for <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The daily said a spot check of industrial products earlier this year found that only 20 percent fully satisfied national standards. Among tractor gears checked, for example, only 13.3 percent met quality specifications.
